/* Brief tooltip descriptions for terms referenced in card backgrounds.
   Keyed by Wikipedia article slug (decoded). Missing terms fall back to the
   humanized slug name at runtime. */
window.GLOSSARY = {
"Qing_dynasty": "China's last imperial dynasty (1644–1912), founded by the Manchus and ended by the Xinhai Revolution. At its height under the Kangxi and Qianlong emperors it ruled a vast, prosperous, multiethnic empire stretching deep into Central Asia. In the nineteenth century it was hollowed out by population pressure, massive rebellions, and a string of defeats by foreign powers.",
"Kuomintang": "The Chinese Nationalist Party, founded by Sun Yat-sen and later led by Chiang Kai-shek. It reunified much of China in the 1920s, governed from Nanjing, and fought both the Japanese invasion and the Communists. After losing the Chinese Civil War in 1949 it withdrew to Taiwan, where it long remained the ruling party.",
"Chinese_Communist_Party": "The party founded in 1921 that won the civil war and has ruled China since 1949. Guided by Marxism adapted to Chinese conditions, it rose through peasant mobilization, the Long March, and the war against Japan. Under leaders from Mao Zedong to Xi Jinping it has held a monopoly on political power for over seven decades.",
"Empire_of_Japan": "The Japanese state from 1868 to 1947, whose expansion brought war across Asia and the Pacific. After the Meiji Restoration it modernized rapidly and defeated both Qing China and Russia in regional wars. Its drive for empire led to the seizure of Manchuria, full-scale war with China, and ultimately defeat in 1945.",
"Beijing": "China's historic northern capital, seat of the imperial court and, since 1949, the People's Republic. Home to the Forbidden City and the Old Summer Palace, it was the political heart of the late Qing empire. Foreign armies occupied it during both the Second Opium War and the Boxer Rebellion.",
"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)": "The republic that replaced the Qing in 1912 and ruled the mainland until the Communist victory in 1949. Its early decades were marked by the failure of Yuan Shikai, the Warlord Era, and fragile Nationalist rule from Nanjing. Defeated in the civil war, its government relocated to Taiwan, where it continues today.",
"Chiang_Kai-shek": "Nationalist (KMT) leader who ruled China from 1928 and retreated to Taiwan after losing the civil war. He rose through the Whampoa Military Academy and the Northern Expedition before purging his Communist allies in 1927. He led China through the war against Japan but was ultimately defeated by Mao's forces.",
"Sun_Yat-sen": "Revolutionary regarded as the founding father of the Chinese republic and the first KMT leader. He spent years in exile organizing against the Qing and articulated the Three Principles of the People. Though he briefly served as provisional president in 1912, real power soon slipped to Yuan Shikai.",
"Nanjing": "City on the Yangtze that served as the Nationalist capital and site of the 1937 Japanese massacre. A former imperial capital, it gave its name to the 1842 Treaty of Nanking and the Nanjing decade of KMT rule. Its capture by Japanese forces was followed by one of the war's worst atrocities.",
"Second_Sino-Japanese_War": "The 1937–1945 war between China and Japan, which merged into World War II. It began with a clash at the Marco Polo Bridge and saw Japan occupy much of eastern China. The conflict cost millions of Chinese lives and forced the Nationalists and Communists into an uneasy united front.",
"Self-Strengthening_Movement": "A late-1800s Qing drive to adopt Western arms and industry while keeping Confucian institutions. Led by officials such as Li Hongzhang and Zeng Guofan, it built arsenals, shipyards, and a modern navy. Its limits were exposed by China's defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War.",
"Mao_Zedong": "Communist leader who founded the People's Republic of China in 1949 and ruled until 1976. He built the party's strength among the peasantry and emerged as paramount leader during the Long March. His later campaigns, including the Great Leap Forward and Cultural Revolution, caused immense upheaval.",
"Unequal_treaty": "Treaties imposed on China by foreign powers granting them one-sided privileges after defeats. Beginning with the Treaty of Nanking, they opened treaty ports, fixed low tariffs, and granted extraterritoriality. To Chinese nationalists they became the central symbol of the century of humiliation.",
"First_Sino-Japanese_War": "The 1894–1895 war in which Japan defeated Qing China and seized Taiwan. Fought mainly over influence in Korea, it shattered the prestige of the Self-Strengthening Movement. The harsh Treaty of Shimonoseki that ended it signaled Japan's rise and China's weakness.",
"Guangzhou": "The southern port (Canton) that was long China's sole gateway for Western trade. Under the Canton System, foreign merchants could trade only there, through the licensed Cohong guild. It was a cradle of revolution, home to the Whampoa Academy and early Nationalist activity.",
"Manchuria": "China's northeast, homeland of the Manchus and later a focus of Japanese and Russian ambitions. Rich in coal, iron, and farmland, it was crossed by competing railways and spheres of influence. Japan seized it after the Mukden Incident and ran it as the puppet state of Manchukuo.",
"Manchu_people": "The northeastern people who conquered China in 1644 and ruled as the Qing dynasty. Organized under the Eight Banners, they formed a privileged military caste atop a largely Han population. Over the centuries many assimilated to Chinese culture even as they upheld Manchu distinctiveness.",
"Boxer_Rebellion": "An anti-foreign, anti-Christian uprising (1899–1901) crushed by an eight-nation expedition. Its fighters, drawn to martial-arts rituals, besieged the foreign legations in Beijing. After foreign armies relieved the siege, the Qing were forced to accept the punishing Boxer Protocol.",
"Taiwan": "The island to which the defeated Nationalists retreated in 1949, still governed by the Republic of China. Ceded to Japan in 1895 and returned to China in 1945, it became the KMT's final stronghold. Its political status remains one of the most sensitive issues in cross-strait relations.",
"Xinhai_Revolution": "The 1911 revolution that toppled the Qing dynasty and founded the Republic of China. Sparked by a military mutiny at Wuchang, it spread as province after province declared independence. It ended more than two millennia of imperial rule and brought Sun Yat-sen briefly to the presidency.",
"Imperial_examination": "The civil-service exam that selected officials by Confucian learning for over a millennium. It offered a path to status based on mastery of the classics rather than birth. The Qing abolished it in 1905, severing a key link between the state and the scholarly elite.",
"Empress_Dowager_Cixi": "The dominant power at the Qing court for nearly fifty years until her death in 1908. Ruling through young emperors, she blocked the Hundred Days' Reform and at first backed the Boxers. Her conservatism is often blamed for the dynasty's failure to modernize in time.",
"Tael": "A traditional Chinese unit of silver weight used as money and for indemnities. Rather than a coin, it was a measure of pure silver that varied somewhat by region. War indemnities to foreign powers were often reckoned in millions of taels.",
"Confucianism": "The ethical and political philosophy of Confucius that underpinned Chinese statecraft and society. It stressed hierarchy, ritual propriety, education, and the duties binding ruler and subject, parent and child. For two thousand years it shaped the imperial examinations and the conduct of officials.",
"Second_Opium_War": "The 1856–1860 war in which Britain and France forced more concessions and burned the Summer Palace. Triggered by trade and diplomatic disputes, it ended Qing resistance to Western demands. The resulting treaties opened more ports, legalized opium, and ceded Kowloon.",
"Puyi": "The last Qing emperor, who abdicated in 1912 and later fronted Japan's puppet state of Manchukuo. Enthroned as a small child, he reigned only briefly before the Xinhai Revolution. After serving as Japan's figurehead, he ended his life as a citizen of the People's Republic.",
"Russian_Empire": "The tsarist empire that expanded into Chinese territory in Manchuria and Central Asia. Through the conventions of the 1850s and 1860s it annexed Outer Manchuria north of the Amur. Its rivalry with Japan over the region led to the Russo-Japanese War.",
"Taiping_Rebellion": "A massive 1850–1864 religious civil war that nearly toppled the Qing and killed tens of millions. Led by Hong Xiuquan, who claimed to be Jesus's brother, it founded a rival kingdom at Nanjing. It was finally crushed by regional armies under Zeng Guofan and Li Hongzhang.",
"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki": "The 1895 treaty ending the First Sino-Japanese War, ceding Taiwan and a huge indemnity to Japan. It also recognized Korean independence and opened new ports to Japanese trade. The Triple Intervention soon forced Japan to return the Liaodong Peninsula it had won.",
"Shanghai": "China's largest port and commercial hub, site of major foreign concessions. Opened by the Treaty of Nanking, it grew into a cosmopolitan center of trade, banking, and industry. Its International Settlement and French Concession operated largely beyond Chinese control.",
"Century_of_humiliation": "The nationalist term for China's era of foreign domination from the Opium Wars to 1949. It frames the unequal treaties, lost wars, and foreign concessions as a national trauma. The narrative remains central to how the People's Republic presents its modern history.",
"Li_Hongzhang": "A leading late-Qing statesman and diplomat who led modernization and negotiated many treaties. He raised the Huai Army against the Taiping and built shipyards, arsenals, and the Beiyang fleet. As the dynasty's chief negotiator, he signed humiliating settlements including Shimonoseki.",
"Warlord_Era": "The years (c. 1916–1928) when regional commanders fought for control of a fragmented China. After Yuan Shikai's death, no government could command the whole country. The chaos ended only when the Northern Expedition reunified China under the Nationalists.",
"First_Opium_War": "The 1839–1842 war in which Britain defeated Qing China and seized Hong Kong. It began when Commissioner Lin Zexu suppressed the illegal British opium trade at Canton. The Treaty of Nanking that followed opened the era of unequal treaties.",
"Opium": "The narcotic whose British-driven trade into China sparked the Opium Wars. Grown in British India, it was smuggled into China in vast quantities, draining silver and spreading addiction. Qing efforts to stamp it out led directly to war and defeat.",
"Yangtze": "China's longest river, a vital artery running from the interior to the sea at Shanghai. Its valley holds many of China's great cities, including Nanjing and Wuhan. Control of its course was strategically vital in nearly every modern conflict.",
"Chinese_Civil_War": "The 1927–1949 struggle between Nationalists and Communists, won by the Communists. Interrupted by the war against Japan, it resumed in full after 1945. Its outcome sent the Nationalists to Taiwan and established the People's Republic on the mainland.",
"First_United_Front": "The 1923–1927 alliance between the KMT and the Communists against the warlords. Brokered with Soviet help, it pooled the two parties' strength for the Northern Expedition. It collapsed when Chiang Kai-shek turned on the Communists in the 1927 Shanghai massacre.",
"Northern_Expedition": "The 1926–1928 KMT military campaign that defeated the warlords and reunified China. Launched from Canton, its armies swept north to take Wuhan, Nanjing, and finally Beijing. Its success established the Nationalist government but also triggered the split with the Communists.",
"Soviet_Union": "The communist state (1922–1991) that advised and backed China's Communists and at times the KMT. Through the Comintern it supplied ideology, money, and military advisers. Relations with Mao's China shifted from alliance in the 1950s to bitter rivalry.",
"Hundred_Days'_Reform": "An abortive 1898 reform program by the Guangxu Emperor, ended by a Cixi-led coup. Inspired by reformers like Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao, it sought sweeping institutional change. After little more than three months, conservatives seized power and executed leading reformers.",
"Yuan_Shikai": "A Beiyang general who became the republic's first president and briefly declared himself emperor. He commanded China's most modern army and forced the Qing abdication in 1912. His 1915 attempt to found a new dynasty collapsed amid revolts and hastened the Warlord Era.",
"National_Revolutionary_Army": "The KMT army that carried out the Northern Expedition and fought Japan. Built with Soviet help and officers from the Whampoa Academy, it became the core of Nationalist power. It bore the brunt of the long war against the Japanese invasion.",
"Treaty_of_Nanking": "The 1842 treaty ending the First Opium War, opening ports and ceding Hong Kong. It forced China to pay an indemnity, fix low tariffs, and open five ports to British trade. As the first of the unequal treaties, it set the template for those that followed.",
"Long_March": "The Communists' 1934–1935 retreat of some 9,000 km that cemented Mao's leadership. Driven from their Jiangxi base by Nationalist encirclement, the Red Army marched to remote Shaanxi. The ordeal became a founding legend of the party and confirmed Mao at its head.",
"Hong_Kong": "The territory ceded to Britain after the Opium Wars and returned to China in 1997. Hong Kong Island, Kowloon, and the New Territories were acquired in successive nineteenth-century agreements. Under British rule it grew into a major port and financial center.",
"Guangxu_Emperor": "The reform-minded Qing emperor (r. 1875–1908) sidelined by Empress Dowager Cixi. He backed the Hundred Days' Reform in a bid to modernize the state. After the reform's failure he spent his final years effectively under house arrest.",
"Boxer_Protocol": "The 1901 settlement imposing a huge indemnity and foreign troop rights after the Boxer Rebellion. It required China to pay 450 million taels over many years and punish officials who had backed the Boxers. It also allowed foreign garrisons along the route from Beijing to the sea.",
"Guangdong": "The southern coastal province around Canton, a center of trade and revolution. Long China's main window on the maritime world, it produced many overseas emigrants. It was a base for Sun Yat-sen's movement and the launch point of the Northern Expedition.",
"Mukden_Incident": "Japan's staged 1931 railway bombing used as a pretext to seize Manchuria. Officers of the Kwantung Army blew up a stretch of track and blamed Chinese troops. Within months Japan had occupied the northeast and set up the puppet state of Manchukuo.",
"Zhou_Enlai": "A leading Communist who became the People's Republic's first premier. A skilled negotiator and administrator, he was central to party affairs from the 1920s onward. He served as premier and foreign minister, shaping China's diplomacy for decades.",
"Communist_International": "The Moscow-led Comintern that directed world communist parties, including China's. It sent advisers and funds and pressed the Chinese Communists into the First United Front. Its strategic directives shaped, and sometimes harmed, the party's early fortunes.",
"Treaty_ports": "Chinese ports opened by treaty to foreign trade and residence under special privileges. Beginning with five after 1842, their number grew to dozens over the following decades. Within them foreigners enjoyed extraterritoriality and ran their own concessions.",
"Convention_of_Peking": "The 1860 agreements ending the Second Opium War, ceding Kowloon and more. Signed after Anglo-French forces occupied Beijing, they confirmed the earlier Treaty of Tientsin. They also legalized the opium trade and ceded territory to Britain and Russia.",
"German_Empire": "Imperial Germany (1871–1918), which held a concession at Qingdao in Shandong. It leased Jiaozhou Bay in 1898 and developed it as a naval and commercial base. Its loss of Shandong rights to Japan after World War I triggered the May Fourth protests.",
"Chongqing": "The wartime capital of Nationalist China during the war with Japan. Perched on the upper Yangtze, it was beyond easy reach of Japanese ground forces. It endured years of heavy aerial bombing as the seat of Chiang's government.",
"May_Fourth_Movement": "The 1919 student protests against the Versailles settlement that sparked cultural renewal. Outrage at the award of Shandong to Japan brought students into the streets of Beijing. It fed a broader New Culture movement promoting science, democracy, and vernacular writing.",
"Nationalist_government": "The KMT-led government of the Republic of China, centered at Nanjing from 1928. It claimed to reunify China but never fully controlled the warlords or the Communists. Weakened by war and corruption, it lost the mainland in 1949.",
"Shanghai_massacre": "Chiang Kai-shek's violent 1927 purge of Communists that ended the First United Front. Nationalist forces and allied gangs killed and arrested Communists across Shanghai. The bloodshed drove the survivors underground and into the countryside.",
"Chinese_Soviet_Republic": "The Communist base state in Jiangxi (1931–1934) led by Mao before the Long March. It ran land reform and its own army in defiance of the Nationalist government. Nationalist encirclement campaigns eventually forced its abandonment.",
"Encirclement_Campaigns": "Nationalist offensives in the early 1930s aimed at destroying the Communist base areas. Successive campaigns tightened a blockade around the Jiangxi Soviet. The fifth and largest finally forced the Communists to break out on the Long March.",
"Second_United_Front": "The uneasy 1937–1945 KMT–Communist alliance against the Japanese invasion. Forged after the Xi'an Incident, it suspended the civil war to resist Japan. Mutual distrust persisted, and the two sides clashed even while nominally allied.",
"United_States": "The major power that mediated and aided China, especially against Japan in World War II. It supplied the Nationalists with arms, loans, and advisers during the war. After 1949 it recognized the Taiwan-based Republic of China for decades.",
"Extraterritoriality": "The privilege exempting foreigners in China from Chinese law, tried instead by their own consuls. Granted by the unequal treaties, it placed foreign residents beyond Chinese courts. Its abolition during World War II was a milestone for Chinese sovereignty.",
"Tianjin": "A major northern treaty port near Beijing, formerly romanized Tientsin. Opened after the Second Opium War, it hosted concessions of many foreign powers. Its proximity to the capital made it strategically important in every northern crisis.",
"Zeng_Guofan": "The Qing official whose Xiang Army suppressed the Taiping Rebellion. He pioneered the regional armies that saved the dynasty from collapse. A devout Confucian, he also promoted early self-strengthening efforts.",
"Peking_University": "Beijing's leading university, a hub of the New Culture and May Fourth movements. Founded in 1898, it became a center of intellectual ferment in the early republic. Many of the era's reformers and radicals taught or studied there.",
"Shaanxi": "The northwestern province where the Communists made Yan'an their base. Its loess hills sheltered the party after the Long March. From there the Communists rebuilt their strength during the war against Japan.",
"Marxism": "The socialist theory of Karl Marx that became the Communist Party's ideological basis. It analyzes history through class struggle and predicts the overthrow of capitalism. Chinese Communists adapted it to a largely peasant society under Mao.",
"Eight_Banners": "The Manchu military-social organization that formed the backbone of Qing power. Banner households supplied soldiers and enjoyed special status and stipends. Over time the system declined, and banner forces lost their early fighting edge.",
"Eight-Nation_Alliance": "The coalition of foreign powers that invaded China to crush the Boxer Rebellion in 1900. Troops from Japan, Russia, Britain, and others marched on Beijing to relieve the besieged legations. Their victory led to the harsh Boxer Protocol.",
"British_Empire": "The global empire whose trade and wars first opened China to Western influence. It fought both Opium Wars, acquired Hong Kong, and dominated early treaty-port commerce. For much of the nineteenth century it was the leading foreign power in China.",
"Sphere_of_influence": "A region where one foreign power claimed special economic and political privileges in China. By the 1890s rival powers had carved out such zones around railways and ports. The scramble raised fears that China would be partitioned outright.",
"Tongmenghui": "Sun Yat-sen's revolutionary alliance (1905) that helped overthrow the Qing. Formed in Tokyo from several anti-Qing groups, it spread revolutionary ideas among students and soldiers. It was a forerunner of the Kuomintang.",
"Manchukuo": "The Japanese puppet state set up in Manchuria in 1932 under the former emperor Puyi. Though presented as independent, it was controlled by Japan's Kwantung Army. It served as a base for Japanese expansion until 1945.",
"Canton_System": "The pre-1842 regime confining Western trade to licensed merchants at Canton. Foreigners could deal only through the Cohong guild and lived under tight restrictions. The First Opium War swept the system away in favor of the treaty ports.",
"Treaty_of_Tientsin": "The 1858 treaties opening more ports and legalizing opium after the Second Opium War. They allowed foreign legations in Beijing and Christian missionaries inland. When the Qing resisted ratification, fighting resumed and led to the Convention of Peking.",
"Zongli_Yamen": "The Qing office created in 1861 to handle foreign affairs, a step toward a foreign ministry. It managed dealings with Western powers during the self-strengthening years. It was later replaced by a full foreign ministry after the Boxer Protocol.",
"Sichuan": "A large, populous province in China's southwest interior. Ringed by mountains and centered on a fertile basin, it long enjoyed relative isolation. Its remoteness made nearby Chongqing a natural wartime refuge.",
"Xianfeng_Emperor": "The Qing emperor (r. 1850–1861) who faced the Taiping Rebellion and the Second Opium War. His reign saw the dynasty pushed to the brink by rebellion and foreign attack. He fled the capital as Anglo-French forces advanced and died soon after.",
"Nanjing_decade": "The relatively stable period of Nationalist rule from Nanjing, 1927–1937. It brought some modernization in finance, infrastructure, and administration. The decade ended with the outbreak of full-scale war with Japan.",
"Treaty_port": "A Chinese port opened by treaty to foreign trade and residence under special privileges. Within its boundaries foreigners enjoyed extraterritoriality and self-governing concessions. Such ports became engines of commerce and conduits for foreign influence.",
"World_War_II": "The global 1939–1945 conflict into which China's war with Japan merged. China's long resistance tied down large Japanese forces on the mainland. Allied victory in 1945 restored Chinese territory but left the country exhausted and divided.",
"Shandong": "The eastern coastal province held in part by Germany and later contested with Japan. Birthplace of Confucius, it became a focus of foreign concessions around Qingdao. The dispute over its status after World War I ignited the May Fourth Movement.",
"Russo-Japanese_War": "The 1904–1905 war, fought largely on Chinese soil, in which Japan defeated Russia. The two powers clashed over control of Manchuria and Korea. Japan's victory stunned the world and confirmed its arrival as a great power.",
"Three_Principles_of_the_People": "Sun Yat-sen's ideology of nationalism, democracy, and people's livelihood. It served as the guiding doctrine of the Kuomintang and the early republic. The three principles aimed to free China from foreign control and build a modern state.",
"Zhang_Xueliang": "The 'Young Marshal' who seized Chiang at Xi'an in 1936 to force resistance to Japan. He had inherited control of Manchuria from his assassinated warlord father. His dramatic act produced the Second United Front against the Japanese.",
"Chinese_Red_Army": "The Communist army of the civil-war years, forerunner of the People's Liberation Army. It grew from rural uprisings into a disciplined force during the Jiangxi years. The Long March and the war with Japan forged it into a formidable army.",
"Yan'an": "The remote Shaanxi town that was the Communist headquarters from 1936 to 1947. There Mao consolidated his leadership and developed his distinctive brand of communism. The 'Yan'an era' became central to the party's revolutionary self-image.",
"Qianlong_Emperor": "The long-reigning Qing emperor (r. 1735–1796) under whom the empire reached its height. He expanded the empire into Central Asia and presided over a flourishing culture. His later years saw growing corruption and the first signs of decline.",
"Tariff": "A tax on imports; China lost control of its own tariffs under the unequal treaties. Treaty terms fixed Chinese duties at a low fixed rate set by foreign agreement. Recovering tariff autonomy became a major goal of Chinese nationalism.",
"Chinese_nationalism": "The modern movement to restore China's strength and sovereignty against foreign domination. Forged in reaction to the unequal treaties and lost wars, it animated reformers and revolutionaries alike. It drove movements from May Fourth to the rise of both the KMT and the Communists.",
"Zuo_Zongtang": "A Qing general and reformer who crushed rebellions and reconquered Xinjiang. He helped suppress the Taiping before leading campaigns in the northwest. A self-strengthener, he founded a major shipyard at Fuzhou.",
"Yixin,_Prince_Gong": "A reformist Qing prince who led the Zongli Yamen and the Tongzhi Restoration. He negotiated with the foreign powers after 1860 and backed cautious modernization. His influence waxed and waned with the court politics around Cixi.",
"Liang_Qichao": "An influential reformer and writer who promoted constitutional change after 1898. A disciple of Kang Youwei, he fled abroad after the Hundred Days' Reform failed. Through his essays he shaped a generation's thinking about nation and reform.",
"Treaty_of_Versailles": "The 1919 peace treaty whose award of Shandong to Japan triggered China's May Fourth protests. China attended the Paris talks as a victor but saw its claims ignored. Outrage at the settlement led China to refuse to sign the treaty.",
"Shandong_Problem": "The dispute over Japan's claim to Germany's former rights in Shandong after WWI. Japan had occupied the German concession during the war and demanded to keep it. The issue inflamed Chinese opinion and was not resolved until the 1920s.",
"Beiyang_Army": "The modern army built by Yuan Shikai that dominated early republican politics. Trained and equipped on Western lines, it was the strongest force of its day. After Yuan's death its commanders splintered into rival warlord factions.",
"Whampoa_Military_Academy": "The KMT military academy near Canton that trained officers of both parties. Founded in 1924 with Soviet help, it was first headed by Chiang Kai-shek. Its graduates led the Northern Expedition and later commanded on both sides of the civil war.",
"Beiyang_government": "The internationally recognized Beijing government run by Beiyang militarists, 1912–1928. It held China's seat abroad but controlled little beyond the north. The Northern Expedition finally swept it away in favor of the Nationalists.",
"Xi'an_Incident": "The 1936 kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek that forced a united front against Japan. Zhang Xueliang detained Chiang to demand he stop fighting the Communists and resist Japan. The crisis ended with an agreement that produced the Second United Front.",
"People's_Liberation_Army": "The Communist armed forces, named in the late 1940s, that won the civil war. Built from the Red Army of the Jiangxi and Yan'an years, it grew into a mass army. Its victories in 1948–49 secured the founding of the People's Republic.",
"China": "The People's Republic of China, the communist state founded in 1949. It emerged from the Communist victory in the civil war under Mao Zedong. Ruled by the Communist Party, it grew over the following decades into a major world power.",
"Cohong": "The guild of licensed Chinese merchants that monopolized foreign trade at Canton. Under the Canton System, all Western commerce passed through its members. The merchants were held responsible for the conduct of the foreigners they dealt with.",
"Tributary_system_of_China": "The hierarchical order in which neighboring states sent tribute to the Chinese emperor. In return they received trade rights and recognition within a Sinocentric world order. The system framed China's foreign relations until the Western treaty system displaced it.",
"Daoguang_Emperor": "The Qing emperor (r. 1820–1850) whose opium crackdown triggered the First Opium War. He appointed Lin Zexu to suppress the British opium trade at Canton. His reign saw the first great defeat that opened the era of unequal treaties.",
"Old_Summer_Palace": "The imperial garden-palace (Yuanmingyuan) looted and burned by Anglo-French forces in 1860. A vast complex of pavilions and gardens, it was a treasure of Qing art. Its destruction became a lasting symbol of foreign aggression.",
"Yunnan": "A southwestern frontier province bordering Southeast Asia. Mountainous and ethnically diverse, it lay at the edge of Qing control. It served as a corridor for trade and, in wartime, for Allied supply routes.",
"Most_favoured_nation": "A treaty clause automatically extending to one power any privilege granted to another. Through it, concessions wrung from China by one nation spread to all. The mechanism multiplied the reach of the unequal treaties.",
"Outer_Manchuria": "The vast region north of the Amur ceded by the Qing to Russia in 1858–1860. The conventions of those years transferred a huge swath of territory to the tsar. Its loss remains a notable example of the era's territorial concessions.",
"Triple_Intervention": "The 1895 pressure by Russia, France, and Germany forcing Japan to return the Liaodong Peninsula. The three powers objected to Japan's gains under the Treaty of Shimonoseki. Japan yielded but resented the rebuff, deepening its rivalry with Russia.",
"Twenty-One_Demands": "Japan's 1915 ultimatum seeking sweeping rights over China. The demands would have reduced China to a near-protectorate of Japan. Public outrage at China's partial acceptance fueled the rising nationalist movement.",
"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service": "The foreign-run agency that collected China's customs revenue from 1854. Led for decades by Britain's Robert Hart, it was efficient but foreign-controlled. Its revenues helped secure the indemnities China owed under the treaties.",
"Foot_binding": "The painful custom of binding girls' feet, widespread until the early 20th century. Practiced for centuries as a mark of status and beauty, it left women disabled. Reformers campaigned against it, and it faded after the fall of the Qing.",
"Huai_Army": "Li Hongzhang's regional army raised to fight the Taiping and Nian rebellions. Modeled on Zeng Guofan's forces, it became one of the dynasty's strongest armies. It later formed part of the foundation for Qing military modernization.",
"Tongzhi_Restoration": "The 1860s Qing effort to revive the dynasty through limited reform after the rebellions. Led by officials such as Prince Gong and Zeng Guofan, it restored order and began modernization. Its gains proved fragile and did not reverse the longer decline.",
"Tan_Sitong": "A radical reformer executed after the failure of the 1898 Hundred Days' Reform. He urged sweeping change and refused to flee when the coup came. His death made him a martyr to the reform cause.",
"Xi'an": "An ancient northwestern capital city, near the Communist base at Yan'an. Once the seat of several great dynasties, it remained a strategic regional center. It gave its name to the 1936 incident that reshaped the war against Japan.",
"Penghu": "The Pescadores islands in the Taiwan Strait, ceded to Japan in 1895. Strategically placed between the mainland and Taiwan, they long guarded the strait. They passed to Japan under the Treaty of Shimonoseki along with Taiwan.",
"French_Third_Republic": "The French regime (1870–1940) that fought the Sino-French War and held concessions in China. It expanded its empire in nearby Indochina and contested influence in southern China. It maintained concessions in cities such as Shanghai and Tianjin.",
"South_Manchuria_Railway": "The Japanese-controlled railway company that anchored Japan's expansion in Manchuria. Acquired from Russia after 1905, it grew into a vast industrial and colonial enterprise. Its guards and interests provided the pretext for the Mukden Incident.",
"Constitutional_monarchy": "A system limiting monarchy by a constitution, briefly attempted in the late Qing. Reformers urged the court to adopt one to save the dynasty after 1905. The Qing announced a gradual plan, but the 1911 revolution overtook it.",
"New_Culture_Movement": "The 1910s–1920s movement promoting science, democracy, and vernacular writing. Centered on Peking University and the magazine New Youth, it attacked Confucian tradition. It fed directly into the May Fourth Movement and the spread of new ideologies.",
"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun": "The prince regent for the child emperor Puyi in the Qing's final years. He took power in 1908 but proved unable to halt the dynasty's collapse. He resigned the regency shortly before the Qing abdication in 1912.",
"Nanjing_Massacre": "The 1937–1938 mass killing and rape of Nanjing's population by Japanese troops. After the city fell, Japanese forces slaughtered tens of thousands of civilians and prisoners. It remains one of the most infamous atrocities of the war and a lasting source of tension.",
"Cai_Yuanpei": "The liberal educator who reformed Peking University into a center of new thought. As its chancellor he welcomed competing ideas and hired bold young scholars. He helped make the university the seedbed of the New Culture and May Fourth movements.",
"Kwantung_Army": "The Japanese army in Manchuria that engineered the region's seizure in 1931. Often acting on its own initiative, it staged the Mukden Incident as a pretext. It became a driving force of Japanese aggression on the continent.",
"Fengtian_clique": "The Manchuria-based warlord faction led by Zhang Zuolin. Backed at times by Japan, it contested control of Beijing in the 1920s. It declined after Zhang's assassination and his son's submission to the Nationalists.",
"New_Youth": "The influential magazine that launched the New Culture Movement. Founded by Chen Duxiu in 1915, it championed science, democracy, and vernacular writing. Its pages introduced many readers to Marxism and other radical ideas.",
"Chen_Duxiu": "A founder of the New Culture Movement and the first leader of the Communist Party. He edited New Youth and helped spread radical ideas among students. He was later ousted from the party leadership and expelled.",
"Li_Dazhao": "An early Chinese Marxist and co-founder of the Communist Party. A Peking University librarian, he was among the first to embrace the Russian Revolution. He was executed by a warlord in 1927.",
"Zhu_De": "The chief Communist military commander and co-founder of the Red Army. He joined Mao in the mountains to build the early Communist forces. He went on to lead Communist armies through the Long March and the wars that followed.",
"Taipei": "The seat of the Republic of China government on Taiwan after 1949. The Nationalists made it their capital following their defeat on the mainland. It became the political and economic center of Taiwan.",
"28_Bolsheviks": "Moscow-trained Chinese Communists who briefly dominated the party before Mao. Returning from study in the Soviet Union, they pushed orthodox Comintern strategy. Their policies were blamed for disasters that led to Mao's rise at Zunyi.",
"Han_Chinese": "China's majority ethnic group, distinct from the ruling Manchus. Making up the great bulk of the population, they were governed by the Manchu Qing. Han identity became a rallying point for anti-Qing nationalism.",
"Kangxi_Emperor": "The long-reigning early Qing emperor (r. 1661–1722) who consolidated the empire. He suppressed rebellions, secured the frontiers, and patronized scholarship. His reign opened the High Qing era of prosperity and expansion.",
"Xinjiang": "China's vast northwestern frontier, reconquered by Zuo Zongtang in the 1870s. A largely Muslim region of deserts and oases, it was made a province in 1884. It remained a strategically sensitive borderland of the empire.",
"Joseon": "The Korean dynasty that was the model tributary state of imperial China. For centuries it acknowledged Chinese suzerainty within the tributary system. Rivalry over its allegiance helped spark the First Sino-Japanese War.",
"Pearl_River_(China)": "The southern river on which Canton and Hong Kong sit. Its delta was the historic gateway for Western trade with China. It remains one of China's busiest and most economically vital regions.",
"Spanish_dollar": "The silver coin widely used as currency in the China trade. Minted from New World silver, it circulated across the Pacific into Chinese ports. Its silver was central to the trade that opium later disrupted.",
"Lin_Zexu": "The Qing commissioner whose 1839 destruction of opium triggered the First Opium War. Sent to Canton to stamp out the drug, he seized and destroyed huge stocks of British opium. His firm stand led Britain to launch the war that opened China.",
"Kowloon": "The mainland district opposite Hong Kong island, ceded to Britain in 1860. It passed to Britain under the Convention of Peking after the Second Opium War. Together with the island and the New Territories it formed British Hong Kong.",
"Green_Standard_Army": "The Han-manned Qing army that supplemented the Manchu banners. Spread across the provinces, it handled policing and local defense. By the nineteenth century it had grown weak and was eclipsed by regional armies.",
"Aisin-Gioro": "The imperial clan of the Qing dynasty. Of Manchu origin, it furnished every Qing emperor from the dynasty's founding. Its last reigning member was the boy emperor Puyi.",
"United_Kingdom": "Britain, the leading power in opening China through the Opium Wars. It fought both wars, took Hong Kong, and dominated the early treaty ports. For much of the century it was the foremost foreign presence in China.",
"Scholar-official": "A member of the educated bureaucratic elite selected by the imperial examinations. Schooled in the Confucian classics, such men staffed the empire's administration. Known in the West as mandarins, they embodied the union of learning and governance.",
"Fujian": "A southeastern coastal province opposite Taiwan. Mountainous and seafaring, it produced many emigrants and traders. Its ports, including Fuzhou and Xiamen, were opened to foreign trade by treaty.",
"New_Territories": "The area leased to Britain for 99 years in 1898, expanding Hong Kong. The lease added the mainland hinterland north of Kowloon. Its 1997 expiry set the timetable for the return of all Hong Kong to China.",
"Treaty_of_Aigun": "The 1858 treaty by which Russia took the north bank of the Amur from the Qing. Exploiting Qing weakness during the Second Opium War, Russia gained a vast territory. It was confirmed and extended by the 1860 Convention of Peking.",
"Shanghai_International_Settlement": "The foreign-run enclave formed by merging Shanghai's British and American concessions. Governed by a council of foreign residents, it lay largely beyond Chinese authority. It became a center of trade, finance, and refuge in modern China.",
"Xiang_Army": "Zeng Guofan's Hunan-based militia army that defeated the Taiping. Raised locally when the regular forces failed, it pioneered the regional armies. Its success made provincial leaders newly powerful within the empire.",
"Nian_Rebellion": "A peasant uprising in northern China (1851–1868) concurrent with the Taiping. Mounted bands raided across the north China plain for nearly two decades. It was finally crushed by Qing commanders such as Li Hongzhang.",
"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin": "The British envoy who ordered the burning of the Old Summer Palace in 1860. He led the Anglo-French expedition that occupied Beijing in the Second Opium War. His order to destroy the palace was meant to punish the Qing court.",
"Tongzhi_Emperor": "The Qing emperor (r. 1861–1875) during whose minority Cixi ruled. He came to the throne as a child after his father Xianfeng's death. His short reign lent its name to the Tongzhi Restoration.",
"Forbidden_City": "The vast imperial palace complex at the heart of Beijing. For nearly five centuries it was the residence of the Ming and Qing emperors. After the Qing fell it became a public museum.",
"Summer_Palace": "The imperial lakeside garden in Beijing rebuilt by Empress Dowager Cixi. She famously funded its restoration with money meant for the navy. It served as a retreat for the Qing court in the dynasty's final decades.",
"Anhui": "An eastern inland province, home of the Huai Army. Straddling the Yangtze and Huai rivers, it was hard hit by the Taiping war. It produced Li Hongzhang and the soldiers of his regional army.",
"Sino-French_War": "The 1884–1885 war over Vietnam that exposed Qing military weakness. France sought to detach Vietnam from China's tributary orbit. Though China fought hard on land, it lost its claim to suzerainty over Vietnam.",
"Foochow_Arsenal": "A Self-Strengthening shipyard and naval school at Fuzhou. Built with French help, it produced warships and trained naval officers. Much of its fleet was destroyed by France in the Sino-French War.",
"Itō_Hirobumi": "Japan's leading statesman, who negotiated the Treaty of Shimonoseki. A principal architect of the Meiji state, he served repeatedly as prime minister. He imposed harsh terms on China after Japan's 1895 victory.",
"Liaodong_Peninsula": "The strategic Manchurian peninsula ceded to, then returned by, Japan in 1895. Japan won it at Shimonoseki but gave it up under the Triple Intervention. Russia soon leased it, deepening the rivalry that led to war.",
"People's_Republic_of_China": "The communist state proclaimed by Mao Zedong in 1949. It was founded after the Communists' victory in the civil war. Ruled by the Communist Party, it has governed mainland China ever since.",
"Written_vernacular_Chinese": "Everyday spoken-style written Chinese promoted over the classical language. Reformers urged its use to make literacy and ideas accessible to ordinary people. Its adoption was a central achievement of the New Culture Movement.",
"Tsinghua_University": "A leading Beijing university founded with returned Boxer indemnity funds. It began as a college preparing students to study in the United States. It grew into one of China's most prestigious institutions.",
"Wuchang_Uprising": "The October 1911 army mutiny that ignited the Xinhai Revolution. Soldiers of the New Army in Wuchang rose against the Qing. Their revolt spread rapidly and brought down the dynasty.",
"Wang_Jingwei": "A KMT leader who defected to head a Japanese-sponsored government in 1940. Once a close associate of Sun Yat-sen, he rivaled Chiang for leadership. His collaboration with Japan made his name a byword for treason.",
"1911_Revolution": "The revolution that overthrew the Qing and established the Chinese republic. Touched off by the Wuchang Uprising, it spread as provinces declared independence. It ended imperial rule and brought Sun Yat-sen briefly to power.",
"Wuhan": "The central Chinese tri-city (including Wuchang) on the Yangtze. A major inland port and industrial center, it commands the middle Yangtze. It was the site of the 1911 uprising and briefly a Nationalist capital.",
"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria": "The USSR's August 1945 offensive that destroyed Japan's army in Manchuria. Launched in the war's final days, it overwhelmed the Kwantung Army. It hastened Japan's surrender and reshaped the postwar contest in the northeast.",
"Zhang_Zuolin": "The Manchurian warlord ('Old Marshal') assassinated by the Japanese in 1928. He ruled the northeast and at times dominated Beijing. The Japanese killed him when he proved insufficiently pliable.",
"Huanggutun_incident": "The 1928 Japanese bombing that killed the warlord Zhang Zuolin. Kwantung Army officers blew up his train as it neared Mukden. His death pushed his son to align Manchuria with the Nationalists.",
"Central_Plains_War": "A massive 1930 war among Nationalist and allied warlord factions. Coalitions led by Feng Yuxiang and others challenged Chiang Kai-shek. Chiang's victory consolidated, but did not complete, Nationalist control.",
"Hu_Shih": "A leading liberal scholar who championed vernacular writing and pragmatism. Educated in the United States, he promoted reform through gradual, scientific means. He was a central figure of the New Culture Movement.",
"Lu_Xun": "The era's foremost writer, famed for satirical stories in vernacular Chinese. His works laid bare the ills of traditional society with biting irony. He became an icon of modern Chinese literature and, later, of the left.",
"October_Revolution": "The 1917 Bolshevik revolution in Russia that inspired Chinese radicals. Lenin's seizure of power offered a model of revolution to colonized peoples. It spurred the spread of Marxism among Chinese intellectuals.",
"Soong_Mei-ling": "Madame Chiang Kai-shek, the influential wife of the Nationalist leader. American-educated and politically active, she promoted the Nationalist cause abroad. She was especially effective in winning support in the United States.",
"Jiangxi": "The southeastern province that hosted the early Communist soviet base. Its hills sheltered the Chinese Soviet Republic in the early 1930s. Nationalist encirclement there forced the Communists onto the Long March.",
"Eighth_Route_Army": "The Communist force nominally under Nationalist command during the war with Japan. Formed from the Red Army under the Second United Front, it waged guerrilla war. It expanded Communist influence across the north during the conflict.",
"Surrender_of_Japan": "Japan's August 1945 capitulation, ending World War II in Asia. It followed the atomic bombings and the Soviet entry into the war. Japan's collapse reopened the contest between Nationalists and Communists in China.",
"Ruijin": "The Jiangxi town that was capital of the Communists' Chinese Soviet Republic. It served as the political center of the Jiangxi base in the early 1930s. The Communists abandoned it when they set out on the Long March.",
"Zunyi_Conference": "The 1935 Long March meeting where Mao gained effective leadership of the party. Held during the retreat, it criticized the previous military leadership. It marked the turning point that put Mao in command.",
"Ming_dynasty": "The Han-Chinese dynasty (1368–1644) that preceded the Qing. It expelled Mongol rule and presided over a flourishing of culture and commerce. Its fall to rebellion and the Manchus brought in the Qing.",
"High_Qing_era": "The 18th-century height of Qing prosperity and territorial expansion. Under the Kangxi, Yongzheng, and Qianlong emperors, the empire reached its peak. Population and wealth surged before decline set in around 1800.",
"Hong_Xiuquan": "The mystic who declared himself Christ's younger brother and led the Taiping Rebellion. After failing the imperial exams, he founded a militant religious movement. His Heavenly Kingdom at Nanjing nearly toppled the Qing.",
"Mongols": "The steppe people of the north, incorporated into the Qing empire. Once rulers of China under the Yuan, they were later organized within the Qing order. Their lands formed a vast frontier zone of the empire.",
"East_India_Company": "The British trading company that dominated the China trade and opium smuggling. For decades it held a monopoly on British commerce with China. Its opium exports from India helped trigger the Opium Wars.",
"Hubei": "A central province on the Yangtze, site of the Wuchang Uprising. It centers on Wuhan, a key inland transport and industrial hub. The 1911 revolt there set off the fall of the Qing.",
"Treaty_of_the_Bogue": "An 1843 supplement to the Treaty of Nanking granting Britain further privileges. It added extraterritoriality and most-favored-nation rights. It rounded out the settlement that ended the First Opium War.",
"Fuzhou": "A southeastern treaty port and naval-arsenal city in Fujian. Opened by the Treaty of Nanking, it became a center of self-strengthening. Its Foochow Arsenal built ships and trained the early Chinese navy.",
"Jardine_Matheson": "A leading British trading firm built on the China and opium trade. It pressed hard for war when the Qing cracked down on opium. It grew into one of the dominant commercial houses of the treaty-port era.",
"Ningbo": "An eastern coastal treaty port south of Shanghai. One of the five ports opened in 1842, it had a long history of foreign trade. It was soon overshadowed by the rapid rise of nearby Shanghai.",
"France": "A major Western power that fought the Opium and Sino-French wars and held concessions in China. It joined Britain in the Second Opium War and took its own treaty privileges. It contested influence in southern China and nearby Indochina.",
"Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor": "Japan's December 1941 strike that brought the United States into World War II. The surprise attack on the US Pacific Fleet widened the war across the Pacific. It linked China's struggle to the global Allied war effort.",
"Battle_of_Shanghai": "The fierce 1937 battle that opened the full-scale war with Japan. Chinese forces resisted for three months before the city fell. The costly fight shattered hopes of a quick Japanese victory.",
"Guangxi": "A southern province bordering Vietnam, cradle of the Taiping Rebellion. Its poverty and unrest gave rise to Hong Xiuquan's movement. It later produced a powerful clique of Nationalist-era generals.",
"Ever_Victorious_Army": "A Western-officered force that helped the Qing defeat the Taiping near Shanghai. Trained on modern lines, it protected the city and aided Qing armies. It was commanded for a time by the British officer Charles Gordon.",
"Charles_George_Gordon": "The British officer who commanded the Ever Victorious Army against the Taiping. His leadership helped the Qing retake key cities near Shanghai. He won the nickname 'Chinese' Gordon for his service in the war.",
"Second_French_Empire": "Napoleon III's France (1852–1870), which joined Britain in the Second Opium War. It pursued empire in Asia and shared in the gains wrung from China. Its forces helped occupy Beijing and burn the Old Summer Palace.",
"Chengde_Mountain_Resort": "The Qing summer retreat north of Beijing where Xianfeng fled in 1860. A sprawling palace and garden complex, it served as a northern capital. Xianfeng died there after fleeing the Anglo-French advance.",
"Empress_Dowager_Ci'an": "Cixi's senior co-regent dowager empress during the Tongzhi reign. The two women ruled jointly on behalf of the child emperor. Her death in 1881 left Cixi as the court's sole dominant figure.",
"Guerrilla_warfare": "Irregular hit-and-run tactics central to the Communists' rural strategy. Mao made it the foundation of a protracted people's war. It allowed weaker forces to wear down stronger enemies in the countryside.",
"Jiangnan_Arsenal": "A major Shanghai arms factory of the Self-Strengthening Movement. It manufactured guns, ammunition, and ships and translated Western technical works. It was among the most ambitious of the dynasty's modernization projects.",
"Viceroy_of_Zhili": "The powerful Qing governor-general of the capital province around Beijing. The post oversaw the region's defense and foreign dealings. Li Hongzhang's long tenure made it one of the empire's most influential offices.",
"Beiyang_Fleet": "The Qing's modern northern navy, destroyed by Japan in 1895. Built up under Li Hongzhang, it was once reckoned among Asia's strongest. Its annihilation in the First Sino-Japanese War exposed the limits of reform.",
"Kang_Youwei": "The Confucian reformer who inspired the 1898 Hundred Days' Reform. He reinterpreted Confucius as a reformer to justify sweeping change. After the reform's failure he fled abroad and turned more conservative.",
"Late_Qing_reforms": "The post-Boxer 'New Policies' that modernized Qing institutions after 1901. They reformed the army, schools, and administration and abolished the old exams. They came too late to save the dynasty from revolution.",
"Robert_Hart,_1st_Baronet": "The Briton who long directed China's Maritime Customs Service. For nearly half a century he ran the foreign-staffed customs administration. He became a trusted, if foreign, fixture of the late Qing state.",
"Chinese_ironclad_Dingyuan": "A German-built battleship, flagship of the Qing Beiyang Fleet. One of the most powerful warships in Asia when acquired, it symbolized self-strengthening. It was lost in the war with Japan in 1895.",
"Chinese_ironclad_Zhenyuan": "A German-built battleship of the Qing Beiyang Fleet. A sister ship of the Dingyuan, it was among China's strongest vessels. It was captured by Japan after the fleet's defeat in 1895.",
"Battle_of_Weihaiwei": "The 1895 battle where Japan destroyed the remnants of the Beiyang Fleet. Japanese forces besieged the naval base by land and sea. Its fall sealed China's defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War.",
"Imperialism": "The expansion of foreign powers' control that carved up Qing China. Through wars, treaties, and spheres of influence, foreign states gained privileges. Resistance to it became a driving force of Chinese nationalism.",
"Manchu_Restoration": "The brief 1917 attempt to restore the boy emperor Puyi to the throne. A loyalist general put Puyi back on the throne for less than two weeks. The episode collapsed quickly and discredited the monarchist cause.",
"Duan_Qirui": "A Beiyang warlord and premier who dominated Beijing politics after Yuan Shikai. Leader of the Anhui clique, he repeatedly held power in the capital. His rule deepened the disorder of the Warlord Era.",
"National_Protection_War": "The 1915–1916 revolt that forced Yuan Shikai to abandon his monarchy. Provinces rose in arms against his bid to crown himself emperor. The uprising shattered his rule and hastened his death.",
"New_Army": "The modernized Qing forces, many of whose soldiers joined the 1911 revolution. Trained and equipped on Western lines, they were the dynasty's hope. Revolutionary ideas spread through their ranks and helped topple the Qing.",
"Tokyo": "Japan's capital and seat of its imperial government. It was the heart of the Meiji state's drive to modernize and expand. Chinese revolutionaries and students gathered there, including Sun Yat-sen's followers.",
"President_of_the_Republic_of_China": "The head of state of the Chinese republic. The office passed from Sun Yat-sen to Yuan Shikai in the republic's first year. It later anchored Nationalist rule and continues on Taiwan.",
"Mikhail_Borodin": "The Soviet adviser who reorganized the KMT along Leninist lines in the 1920s. Sent by the Comintern, he restructured the party and its army. His work shaped the First United Front and the Northern Expedition.",
"Feng_Yuxiang": "The 'Christian General,' a shifting warlord of the republican era. Known for converting his troops and changing sides, he commanded large forces. He played a pivotal, unpredictable role in the wars among the warlords.",
"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)": "Yuan Shikai's short-lived bid to make himself emperor. He proclaimed a new imperial dynasty with himself on the throne. Fierce opposition forced him to abandon the scheme within months.",
"Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident": "The July 1937 clash near Beijing that began full-scale war with Japan. A minor confrontation between troops escalated into open conflict. It opened eight years of total war between China and Japan.",
"Zhili_clique": "The warlord faction based in the capital region around Beijing. It vied with rival cliques for control of the Beiyang government. Its defeats in the 1920s helped clear the way for the Northern Expedition.",
"Wu_Peifu": "A leading general of the Zhili warlord clique. Once among the most powerful of the warlords, he dominated central China. His fortunes fell as the Nationalists advanced in the Northern Expedition.",
"Joseph_Stalin": "The Soviet leader whose policies shaped Comintern advice to China. His directives influenced the Chinese Communists' strategy and alliances. His distrust and shifting line at times worked against Mao's party.",
"Lin_Biao": "A brilliant Communist commander in the war with Japan and the civil war. He led decisive campaigns that helped win the northeast. He later rose high in the People's Republic before a dramatic fall.",
"Bo_Gu": "A Soviet-trained Communist leader displaced by Mao at the Zunyi Conference. One of the 28 Bolsheviks, he had directed party policy before the Long March. His military failures led to his eclipse by Mao.",
"Otto_Braun_(communist)": "The Comintern military adviser blamed for the Communists' 1934 defeats. The only foreigner on the Long March, he had pushed rigid conventional tactics. His strategy's failure helped bring Mao to power at Zunyi.",
"New_Fourth_Army": "A Communist force in central China that clashed with Nationalists in 1941. Operating south of the Yangtze, it expanded Communist influence during the war. A Nationalist ambush of it badly strained the Second United Front.",
"Pacific_War": "The 1941–1945 World War II theatre between Japan and the Allies. It opened with Pearl Harbor and spanned the Pacific and East Asia. China's long resistance formed a major front of this wider war.",
"Nanchang_uprising": "The August 1927 Communist revolt marking the birth of the Red Army. Communist troops briefly seized the city of Nanchang. Though soon defeated, it is celebrated as the founding of the Communist army.",
"George_Marshall": "The US general who tried and failed to mediate China's civil war in 1946. He sought a coalition between Nationalists and Communists. His mission collapsed as full-scale civil war resumed.",
"Maoism": "Mao Zedong's adaptation of Marxism stressing peasant-based revolution. It held that rural guerrilla war could encircle and capture the cities. It became the guiding ideology of the Chinese revolution.",
"Marxism–Leninism": "The Soviet-derived communist ideology adopted by the Chinese party. It combined Marx's class theory with Lenin's model of a vanguard party. It provided the framework Mao would adapt to Chinese conditions.",
"Yongzheng_Emperor": "The Qing emperor (r. 1722–1735) known for centralizing reforms. He tightened control of finances and administration between two long reigns. His efficient rule helped sustain the High Qing's strength.",
"Emperor_of_China": "The supreme ruler of imperial China, styled the Son of Heaven. He held authority sanctioned by the Mandate of Heaven over all under heaven. The institution ended with the abdication of the last Qing emperor in 1912.",
"Mandate_of_Heaven": "The doctrine that Heaven grants and can withdraw the right to rule. A just ruler held the mandate, while misrule justified rebellion. It legitimized dynasties and explained their fall throughout Chinese history.",
"Suzerainty": "A dominant state's authority over a subordinate one that keeps internal autonomy. China exercised it over tributary states within its world order. The concept clashed with Western ideas of sovereignty in the nineteenth century.",
"Macartney_Embassy": "Britain's 1793 mission that failed to open China to wider trade. Lord Macartney sought diplomatic and commercial relations with the Qianlong court. The emperor rebuffed his requests, deeming Britain a distant tributary.",
"Thirteen_Factories": "The riverside foreign trading houses at Canton under the old system. They were the only quarters where Westerners could live and trade. They formed the cramped heart of the pre-treaty Canton System.",
"Macau": "The Portuguese-administered enclave near Canton, Europe's oldest foothold in China. Held by Portugal from the sixteenth century, it long served as a trade base. It was returned to Chinese rule in 1999, two years after Hong Kong.",
"Tea": "The Chinese export whose huge demand drove the silver-and-opium trade imbalance. British thirst for it sent vast quantities of silver flowing to China. To reverse the drain, Britain pushed opium sales into China.",
"Silk": "A prized Chinese export long sought by foreign traders. For centuries it was among the goods that drew merchants along the Silk Road. It remained a staple of the China trade into the modern era.",
"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen": "Lin Zexu's 1839 public destruction of seized opium that triggered war with Britain. He had thousands of chests of confiscated opium dissolved and flushed away. Britain used the act as a pretext for the First Opium War.",
"Millenarianism": "Belief in a coming age of renewal, a theme of the Taiping and White Lotus revolts. Such hopes inspired mass movements against the Qing order. They lent religious fervor to some of the era's great rebellions.",
"Gansu": "A northwestern province, scene of Muslim revolts suppressed by Zuo Zongtang. A corridor between China proper and Central Asia, it saw harsh fighting. Its pacification preceded the reconquest of Xinjiang.",
"Grand_Canal_(China)": "The great north–south waterway carrying tribute grain to the capital. For centuries it linked the rice-rich south to the northern court. Its decline in the nineteenth century reflected the dynasty's broader troubles.",
"Charles_Elliot": "The British superintendent at Canton whose actions helped spark the First Opium War. He surrendered British opium to Lin Zexu, then sought redress by force. His handling of the crisis drew Britain into war.",
"Jinshi": "The highest degree in the imperial examinations, qualifying men for top office. Winning it crowned years of study of the Confucian classics. Its holders filled the senior ranks of the imperial bureaucracy.",
"Xiamen": "A southeastern treaty port (Amoy) in Fujian. One of the five ports opened in 1842, it had long traded overseas. It became a hub for emigration and foreign commerce.",
"Treaty_of_Wanghia": "The 1844 treaty granting the United States the privileges Britain won at Nanking. It extended extraterritoriality and most-favored-nation rights to Americans. It drew the United States into the unequal-treaty system.",
"Treaty_of_Whampoa": "The 1844 treaty extending to France the privileges won by Britain in China. Signed near Canton, it granted France extraterritoriality and trade rights. It also secured tolerance for Catholic missionaries in China.",
"Concessions_in_China": "Districts of Chinese cities leased to and governed by foreign powers. Within them foreign authorities ran their own courts, police, and administration. They became visible emblems of China's lost sovereignty.",
"Handover_of_Hong_Kong": "Britain's 1997 return of Hong Kong to Chinese sovereignty. It followed the expiry of the lease on the New Territories. Under 'one country, two systems,' Hong Kong was promised a high degree of autonomy.",
"Weihaiwei_under_British_rule": "The northern port leased to Britain from 1898 to 1930. Britain took it to balance Russia's and Germany's gains in the region. It was returned to China after three decades of colonial administration.",
"Hankou": "A Yangtze port (part of Wuhan) that held foreign concessions. A major inland trade hub, it drew British, Russian, and other settlements. It later merged with neighboring cities to form Wuhan.",
"Robert_Hart_(diplomat)": "The Briton who long directed China's Maritime Customs Service. For nearly half a century he ran the foreign-staffed customs administration. He became a trusted, if foreign, fixture of the late Qing state.",
"Shanghai_French_Concession": "The French-governed district of Shanghai. Administered separately from the International Settlement, it had its own police and rules. Known for its tree-lined streets, it became a fashionable quarter of the city.",
"Shanghai_Municipal_Council": "The foreign-run governing body of Shanghai's International Settlement. Elected by foreign ratepayers, it governed the enclave largely without Chinese input. It controlled the settlement's police, finances, and public works.",
"The_Bund": "Shanghai's famous riverfront of foreign banks and trading houses. Its grand buildings symbolized the city's role as a center of finance and trade. It became the iconic face of treaty-port Shanghai.",
"Austria-Hungary": "The Central European empire that joined the Eight-Nation Alliance against the Boxers. It contributed forces to the 1900 expedition that relieved Beijing. Like the others, it gained a small concession at Tianjin.",
"Kingdom_of_Italy": "Italy, a member of the Eight-Nation Alliance with a small Tianjin concession. It joined the powers that crushed the Boxer Rebellion. Its earlier bid for a separate Chinese leasehold had been rebuffed.",
"Beijing_Legation_Quarter": "The foreign diplomatic district in Beijing besieged during the Boxer Rebellion. Its legations held out under attack until an international force relieved them. The siege became the dramatic centerpiece of the Boxer crisis.",
"World_War_I": "The 1914–1918 war whose peace settlement sparked China's May Fourth Movement. China joined the Allies and sent laborers to the Western Front. Its anger at the Versailles award of Shandong to Japan fueled mass protest.",
"Hakka_people": "A Han subgroup from which many Taiping leaders, including Hong Xiuquan, came. Migrants known for distinct customs, they often clashed with their neighbors. Their grievances helped fuel the Taiping Rebellion.",
"God_Worshipping_Society": "Hong Xiuquan's Christian-inspired sect that grew into the Taiping movement. It blended biblical ideas with Hong's claim to be Christ's brother. From its base in Guangxi it swelled into a mass rebellion.",
"Jintian_Uprising": "The 1851 revolt in Guangxi that launched the Taiping Rebellion. Hong Xiuquan's followers rose against the Qing and proclaimed a new kingdom. It began the most destructive civil war of the century.",
"Tianjing_Incident": "The bloody 1856 internal purge that crippled the Taiping leadership. Rival Taiping leaders turned on one another in a deadly power struggle. The slaughter fatally weakened the movement from within.",
"Yang_Xiuqing": "A dominant Taiping leader killed in the movement's 1856 internal bloodletting. He had claimed to speak with the voice of God and overshadowed Hong. His murder in the Tianjing Incident shattered the rebellion's unity.",
"Hong_Rengan": "A reform-minded Taiping leader who proposed modernizing the rebel state. A cousin of Hong Xiuquan, he drafted a program of Western-style reforms. His plans came too late to save the failing movement.",
"Frederick_Townsend_Ward": "The American who founded the Western-led force later called the Ever Victorious Army. He organized foreign-officered troops to defend Shanghai from the Taiping. He was killed in action before his force won its greatest victories.",
"Panthay_Rebellion": "A Muslim revolt in Yunnan (1856–1873) against Qing rule. Led by the region's Muslims, it briefly established an independent state. It was crushed with great bloodshed by Qing forces.",
"Communism": "The revolutionary ideology of collective ownership adopted by Mao's party. It calls for abolishing private property and class to build a classless society. In China it was reshaped by Mao into a peasant-based revolution.",
"Xinyou_Coup": "The 1861 palace coup that brought Empress Dowager Cixi to power. After Xianfeng's death, Cixi and Prince Gong ousted the regents he had named. The coup set Cixi on her decades-long domination of the court.",
"Taku_Forts": "The forts guarding Tianjin, repeatedly stormed by foreign forces in the Opium Wars. They defended the river approach to Beijing from the sea. Their capture opened the way for foreign armies to march on the capital.",
"Hunan": "A central province, home of Zeng Guofan's Xiang Army and, later, Mao Zedong. Its men formed the militia that defeated the Taiping. The province produced many leaders of both the Qing revival and the revolution.",
"Chinese_Educational_Mission": "An 1870s program sending Chinese boys to study in the United States. Part of self-strengthening, it aimed to train experts in Western skills. The Qing recalled the students early amid conservative misgivings.",
"Tongwen_Guan": "A Qing school founded in 1862 to train interpreters and teach Western subjects. Attached to the Zongli Yamen, it taught foreign languages and science. It was an early step toward modern education in China.",
"Zhang_Zhidong": "A reforming late-Qing governor-general and Self-Strengthening industrialist. He built ironworks, arsenals, and railways in central China. He sought to graft Western technology onto Confucian foundations.",
"Ironclad_warship": "An armored steam warship; modern examples anchored the Qing's new navy. Such vessels marked the cutting edge of nineteenth-century sea power. China bought them abroad to build its Beiyang Fleet.",
"China_Merchants_Steam_Navigation_Company": "An 1872 Self-Strengthening shipping enterprise. Backed by Li Hongzhang, it ran steamers to compete with foreign lines. It was a flagship project of state-sponsored modernization.",
"Battle_of_Fuzhou": "The 1884 clash in which France destroyed China's Fujian fleet. A French squadron annihilated the Chinese ships in minutes. The disaster opened the Sino-French War and exposed China's naval weakness.",
"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)": "The 1894 naval battle in which Japan crippled the Beiyang Fleet. Japan's faster, better-led ships outfought the Chinese squadron. The defeat foreshadowed China's loss in the First Sino-Japanese War.",
"Chinese_Eastern_Railway": "The Russian-built railway across Manchuria linking to Vladivostok. It extended Russian influence deep into China's northeast. It became a focus of the rivalry that led to the Russo-Japanese War.",
"Lüshunkou_District": "Port Arthur, the strategic Manchurian naval base fought over by Japan and Russia. Its fortified harbor commanded the approaches to Beijing and Manchuria. Both Japan and Russia coveted and seized it in turn.",
"Taiwan_under_Japanese_rule": "Japan's colonial rule of Taiwan from 1895 to 1945. Won at Shimonoseki, the island was Japan's first major colony. Japan developed its economy while suppressing local resistance.",
"Wilhelm_II,_German_Emperor": "Germany's emperor whose 'Yellow Peril' talk accompanied its seizure of Qingdao. He pushed an aggressive policy of overseas expansion. Under him Germany took its Shandong leasehold in 1898.",
"Kwantung_Leased_Territory": "The Liaodong tip leased to Japan, base of its Kwantung Army. Japan acquired it after defeating Russia in 1905. From there it projected power across Manchuria.",
"Qingdao": "The Shandong port developed as a German colony, later seized by Japan. Germany built it into a model port and naval base. Its fate after World War I ignited the May Fourth protests.",
"Eight-legged_essay": "The rigidly formatted essay required in the imperial examinations. Its strict eight-part structure tested mastery of Confucian texts. Critics blamed it for stifling original thought.",
"Empress_Dowager_Longyu": "The dowager empress who signed the boy emperor Puyi's abdication in 1912. Acting for the child emperor, she accepted the terms ending Qing rule. Her signature closed more than two millennia of imperial government.",
"Zhongnanhai": "The former imperial garden in Beijing that became China's seat of government. Adjoining the Forbidden City, it houses the Communist leadership. It is the political nerve center of the People's Republic.",
"New_Policies": "The Qing's post-1901 reforms of its army, schools, and administration. Adopted after the Boxer disaster, they modernized many institutions. They came too late to forestall the 1911 revolution.",
"Sexagenary_cycle": "The traditional 60-year cycle of Chinese dating (as in 'Xinhai'). It pairs ten heavenly stems with twelve earthly branches. Years like 'Xinhai' 1911 take their names from this cycle.",
"Anti-imperialism": "Opposition to foreign domination, a driving force of modern Chinese politics. It united reformers, nationalists, and Communists against the unequal treaties. The demand to end foreign privilege shaped the era's movements.",
"Shanxi": "A northern province (distinct from Shaanxi), long ruled by the warlord Yan Xishan. Rich in coal, it was a stronghold of one of the era's most durable warlords. Its mountains made it a natural fortress in the civil wars.",
"Clemens_von_Ketteler": "The German minister whose murder in 1900 helped trigger the Boxer expedition. He was killed in the streets of Beijing as the crisis flared. His death galvanized the foreign powers' military response.",
"Railway_Protection_Movement": "The 1911 protests over railway nationalization that helped spark the revolution. Anger at the Qing plan to seize local railways spread across provinces. The unrest, especially in Sichuan, opened the way for the Xinhai Revolution.",
"Song_Jiaoren": "A KMT leader and parliamentary champion assassinated in 1913. He built the Nationalists into a winning electoral party. His murder, widely blamed on Yuan Shikai, ended hopes for parliamentary rule.",
"Second_Revolution_(China)": "The failed 1913 revolt against Yuan Shikai's growing power. Nationalists rose in arms after Song Jiaoren's assassination. Its defeat left Yuan dominant and drove KMT leaders into exile.",
"Democracy": "Rule by the people, a central ideal of the New Culture and republican movements. Reformers hailed it, alongside science, as a key to national renewal. Its promise repeatedly clashed with the reality of warlord and one-party rule.",
"Li_Yuanhong": "A reluctant figurehead of the 1911 revolution who twice served as president. Pressed into leadership at Wuchang, he became a compromise choice. His presidencies were buffeted by the era's warlord struggles.",
"Feng_Guozhang": "A Beiyang general who briefly served as president of the republic. A leading figure of the Zhili clique, he held power after Yuan Shikai. His tenure was part of the revolving door of warlord-era politics.",
"Allies_of_World_War_II": "The wartime coalition, including China, that defeated the Axis powers. China's long resistance to Japan made it one of the major Allied nations. Allied victory in 1945 restored Chinese territory lost to Japan.",
"United_Nations": "The postwar world body of which China became a founding member in 1945. China took a permanent seat on its Security Council. That seat was held by the Republic of China until 1971.",
"Paris_Peace_Conference_(1919–1920)": "The WWI peace talks whose Shandong decision sparked the May Fourth protests. China came as a victor but saw Japan awarded Germany's Shandong rights. The outrage led China to refuse to sign the Versailles treaty.",
"Guizhou": "A poor southwestern province crossed by the Communists on the Long March. Its rugged terrain sheltered the marchers during their retreat. The Zunyi Conference, which raised Mao, was held there.",
"First_Zhili–Fengtian_War": "The 1922 war between the Zhili and Fengtian warlord cliques. The Zhili clique drove its rivals back into Manchuria. It was one of the major conflicts of the Warlord Era.",
"Second_Zhili–Fengtian_War": "The 1924 war in which the Fengtian clique seized Beijing. A betrayal within the Zhili ranks turned the tide. The victory gave the Manchurian warlords control of the capital.",
"Northeast_Flag_Replacement": "Zhang Xueliang's 1928 pledge of allegiance that nominally reunified China. He raised the Nationalist flag over Manchuria after his father's murder. The gesture completed the Northern Expedition's reunification on paper.",
"Classical_Chinese": "The terse literary language of the elite, displaced by vernacular writing. For millennia it was the medium of scholarship and administration. Reformers pushed it aside in favor of everyday written Chinese.",
"Pragmatism": "The philosophy, championed by Hu Shih, stressing practical results over dogma. Imported from America, it urged testing ideas by their consequences. It shaped liberal currents within the New Culture Movement.",
"Academia_Sinica": "China's national academy of sciences, founded in 1928. It organized research across the sciences and humanities. It became the leading scholarly institution of the republic.",
"Autumn_Harvest_Uprising": "Mao's failed 1927 peasant revolt that led him to build a rural base. The poorly armed rising was quickly crushed. Its failure pushed Mao toward guerrilla war from the countryside.",
"White_Terror_(Taiwan)": "The long political repression on Taiwan under Nationalist martial law. Thousands were jailed or killed as suspected dissidents or Communists. The era of suppression lasted for decades after 1949.",
"Chiang_Ching-kuo": "Chiang Kai-shek's son and successor as leader of Taiwan. He oversaw rapid economic growth and, late in life, political liberalization. His reforms began Taiwan's transition toward democracy.",
"New_Life_Movement": "Chiang Kai-shek's 1934 campaign to instill Confucian discipline and morality. It promoted cleanliness, order, and traditional virtue among citizens. It aimed to strengthen the nation against decadence and communism.",
"Zhang_Guotao": "A Communist founder and Mao rival who later defected to the Nationalists. He commanded his own army and challenged Mao during the Long March. His defeat in their power struggle drove him from the party.",
"Hans_von_Seeckt": "The German general who advised Chiang's army against the Communists. He helped design the blockade strategy of the encirclement campaigns. His methods squeezed the Communists out of their Jiangxi base.",
"Deng_Xiaoping": "A Communist veteran who later led China's market reforms from 1978. He survived purges under Mao to emerge as paramount leader. His 'reform and opening' transformed China's economy.",
"Chongqing_Negotiations": "The 1945 postwar talks between Chiang Kai-shek and Mao Zedong that failed to prevent civil war. The two leaders met to seek a peaceful settlement. Mutual distrust doomed the talks and war soon resumed.",
"Marshall_Mission": "US General George Marshall's failed 1945–1947 effort to mediate between Nationalists and Communists. He pressed both sides toward a coalition government. The mission collapsed as full-scale civil war broke out.",
"Cross-Strait_relations": "The fraught relationship between mainland China and Taiwan since 1949. Both governments long claimed to be the rightful ruler of all China. The dispute over Taiwan's status remains deeply contentious.",
"Wang_Ming": "A Moscow-backed Communist leader and rival whom Mao sidelined. A leader of the 28 Bolsheviks, he pushed the Comintern line. He lost out to Mao in the struggle for control of the party.",
"Karl_Marx": "The German philosopher whose theory of class struggle founded modern communism. He argued that history advances through conflict between classes. His ideas became the bedrock of the Chinese Communist Party.",
"Vladimir_Lenin": "The leader of Russia's 1917 Bolshevik Revolution and founder of the Soviet state. He adapted Marxism into a doctrine of vanguard-party revolution. His model deeply influenced the organization of China's Communists.",
"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement": "Mao's early-1940s campaign to consolidate ideological control over the Communist Party. It enforced conformity to Mao's line through study and self-criticism. It cemented his dominance over party thought.",
"New_Democracy": "Mao's 1940 program for a transitional, multi-class stage before socialism. It proposed an alliance of classes under Communist leadership. It guided party strategy around the founding of the People's Republic.",
"Cultural_Revolution": "Mao's turbulent 1966–1976 campaign of radical upheaval and persecution. He mobilized youth to attack perceived enemies within the party. The decade of chaos brought violence, purges, and lasting trauma.",
"Jurchen_people": "The Manchurian people whose tribes Nurhaci united to found the Qing's forerunner state. A Tungusic people of the northern forests, they had once ruled north China. Reorganized as the Manchus, they would conquer all of China.",
"Nurhaci": "The Jurchen chieftain who unified the Manchu tribes and founded the Later Jin in 1616. He created the Eight Banners that became the Qing war machine. His state laid the foundation for the conquest of China.",
"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)": "The Manchu state founded by Nurhaci in 1616, renamed the Qing in 1636. It united the Jurchen tribes and challenged the Ming on the frontier. Under Nurhaci's heirs it grew into the empire that took China.",
"Hong_Taiji": "Nurhaci's son, who proclaimed the Qing dynasty and the Manchu identity in the 1630s. He renamed his people the Manchus and his state the Qing. He prepared the way for the conquest completed after his death.",
"Li_Zicheng": "The rebel whose capture of Beijing in 1644 ended the Ming dynasty. His peasant army seized the capital as the Ming collapsed. His brief triumph opened the door to the Manchu conquest.",
"Wu_Sangui": "The Ming general who opened the Great Wall's gate to the Manchu armies in 1644. He let the Qing forces through to crush the rebel Li Zicheng. His defection helped seal the fall of the Ming.",
"Shanhai_Pass": "The strategic Great Wall gateway through which the Manchus entered China in 1644. Where the wall meets the sea, it guarded the route into China proper. Its opening by Wu Sangui let the Qing armies pour south.",
"Dorgon": "The Manchu regent who directed the Qing conquest of China after 1644. Ruling for the boy emperor Shunzhi, he led the armies that took the country. He set many of the policies of early Qing rule.",
"Shunzhi_Emperor": "The first Qing emperor to reign over China, installed as a boy in 1644. His uncle Dorgon governed during his minority. His reign saw the consolidation of Manchu rule over the former Ming lands.",
"Northeast_China": "Manchuria, the northeastern region that was the Manchu homeland. Rich in resources, it became a prize for Russian and Japanese ambitions. It was the base from which the Qing conquered China.",
"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)": "The earlier Jurchen dynasty that ruled north China before the Mongols. Founded by the ancestors of the Manchus, it conquered the north. It was destroyed by the rising power of the Mongols.",
"Kowtow": "The ritual kneeling and bowing demanded as submission before the Chinese emperor. Envoys were expected to perform it to acknowledge his supremacy. Western refusals to kowtow symbolized clashing ideas of equality.",
"Tang_dynasty": "A golden-age Chinese dynasty (618–907) often invoked as a cultural high point. It presided over a cosmopolitan empire of poetry, art, and trade. Later Chinese looked back on it as a model of greatness.",
"Westphalian_sovereignty": "The European principle of equal sovereign states that clashed with China's tributary order. It held that states are formally equal and independent. Its imposition undermined China's hierarchical world view.",
"Chinese_export_porcelain": "Fine Chinese ceramics produced in huge quantities for the Western market. Prized in Europe, it was a staple of the early China trade. Its export reflected the long Western appetite for Chinese goods.",
"Free_trade": "The doctrine of unrestricted commerce that Western merchants pressed on Qing China. Britain invoked it to demand the opening of Chinese ports. It became a rallying cry behind the push that led to the Opium Wars.",
"Customs": "Duties levied on goods at the border; China's were managed by a foreign-run service. The treaties stripped China of control over its own tariffs. A foreign-led customs agency collected the revenue for decades.",
"White_Lotus": "A clandestine millenarian Buddhist tradition behind several anti-Qing revolts. Its secret societies promised salvation and resisted the state. Its great rebellion strained the Qing around 1800.",
"Jiaqing_Emperor": "The Qing emperor (r. 1796–1820) who faced the costly White Lotus Rebellion. He battled corruption inherited from the late Qianlong years. His reign marked the start of the dynasty's nineteenth-century decline.",
"Temple_name": "The honorific name given to a Chinese emperor for use in ancestral worship. Bestowed after death, it differed from the reign name used in life. Emperors are often known to history by these names.",
"Yellow_River": "China's second-longest river and the cradle of early Chinese civilization, long nicknamed 'China's Sorrow' for its devastating floods. Carrying immense loads of yellow loess silt, it built its bed above the surrounding plain and repeatedly burst its dikes, shifting course many times across history. Taming its waters has been a central task of Chinese statecraft for millennia.",
"Hanlin_Academy": "The elite imperial academy of top examination graduates who advised the throne. Its members drafted documents and compiled official histories. Membership marked the summit of a scholar's career.",
"Viceroy_of_Huguang": "The Qing governor-general overseeing the central provinces of Hubei and Hunan. The post commanded a strategic stretch of the middle Yangtze. Zhang Zhidong made it a center of late-Qing reform.",
"Steamship": "The steam-powered vessel whose military use gave Western navies a decisive edge. Gunboats could move against wind and current up China's rivers. Their power made resistance to Western forces far harder.",
"Hong_Kong_Island": "The island ceded to Britain in 1842, the core of colonial Hong Kong. Its deep harbor made it a prized base for trade and shipping. From it Britain expanded its hold over the surrounding territory.",
"Jiaozhou_Bay_Leased_Territory": "The Shandong bay leased to Germany in 1898, centered on Qingdao. Germany developed it as a naval base and model colony. Its transfer to Japan after World War I provoked the May Fourth protests.",
"The_Hongkong_and_Shanghai_Banking_Corporation": "HSBC, the British bank founded in 1865 to finance the China trade. It bankrolled commerce and lent to the Chinese government. It became the leading financial institution of the treaty-port world.",
"Yokohama": "The Japanese treaty port that became a model of foreign-settlement commerce. Opened to the West, it grew into a thriving international harbor. Its example influenced the development of China's treaty ports.",
"Korea": "China's key tributary neighbor, lost to Japanese influence after 1895. For centuries it had acknowledged Chinese suzerainty. Rivalry over it triggered the First Sino-Japanese War.",
"British_Supreme_Court_for_China": "The British court in Shanghai that tried UK subjects under extraterritoriality. It applied British law to British residents in China. It embodied the legal privileges granted by the unequal treaties.",
"Shanghai_Mixed_Court": "The Shanghai tribunal where foreign assessors sat in judgment over Chinese cases. Foreign officials shared in trying Chinese within the settlements. It became a symbol of compromised Chinese sovereignty.",
"Ottoman_Empire": "The declining Muslim empire often likened to Qing China as a 'sick man'. Both were vast old empires beset by foreign pressure and reform struggles. The comparison underscored fears of partition and collapse.",
"Shanghai_Municipal_Police": "The police force of Shanghai's foreign-run International Settlement. It maintained order in the enclave under foreign command. It enforced the authority of the Municipal Council.",
"White_émigré": "Anti-Bolshevik Russians who fled to China, many settling in Shanghai and Harbin. They left Russia after the Bolsheviks won their civil war. Their communities added to the cosmopolitan mix of China's cities.",
"Jiujiang": "A Yangtze treaty port in Jiangxi with a former British concession. It served as a river outlet for the tea trade. Like other ports, it hosted a foreign settlement under treaty rights.",
"Shanghai_Ghetto": "The district of occupied Shanghai where Jewish refugees were confined during WWII. Thousands fleeing Nazi Europe found shelter, then restriction, there. It became a notable haven amid the wider catastrophe.",
"Wang_Jingwei_regime": "The Japanese-backed puppet government Wang Jingwei led from Nanjing, 1940–1945. It claimed to be the legitimate Nationalist government. In reality it served Japanese aims in occupied China.",
"Green_Gang": "The Shanghai criminal syndicate that aided Chiang's 1927 purge of Communists. It dominated the city's underworld of opium and racketeering. Its gangsters helped carry out the Shanghai massacre.",
"Du_Yuesheng": "The Green Gang boss who helped Chiang Kai-shek crush the Shanghai Communists. He commanded the city's underworld and its labor rackets. His gang's muscle was central to the 1927 purge.",
"May_Thirtieth_Movement": "The 1925 anti-foreign protests sparked by a shooting of demonstrators in Shanghai. Foreign police killed Chinese protesters, igniting nationwide outrage. The movement boosted both the Nationalists and the Communists.",
"Reorganized_National_Government_of_the_Republic_of_China": "Wang Jingwei's Japanese-sponsored regime based in Nanjing. It posed as the true Nationalist government during the war. It governed occupied areas on Japan's behalf.",
"Jesus": "The central figure of Christianity, whom the Taiping leader claimed as his elder brother. Hong Xiuquan built his movement around this startling claim. The belief gave the Taiping their militant religious zeal.",
"Christianity": "The religion whose ideas, filtered through Hong Xiuquan, shaped the Taiping movement. Missionary tracts inspired Hong's idiosyncratic faith. His version drove one of history's bloodiest civil wars.",
"Liang_Fa": "An early Chinese Protestant whose tract influenced Hong Xiuquan's Taiping beliefs. His Christian pamphlet fell into Hong's hands after his exam failures. Its ideas helped shape the Taiping's religious vision.",
"Feng_Yunshan": "An early organizer of the Taiping movement in Guangxi. He built up the God Worshipping Society's following in the hills. His groundwork prepared the ground for the 1851 uprising.",
"Shi_Dakai": "A talented Taiping commander who broke away after the movement's internal purge. Disillusioned by the Tianjing Incident, he led his army off on its own. He was eventually captured and executed by the Qing.",
"Taiping_Heavenly_Kingdom": "The rebel theocratic state the Taiping established at Nanjing, 1853–1864. It ruled much of the Yangtze valley under Hong Xiuquan's creed. Its fall after a long siege ended the great rebellion.",
"Prince_Gong": "The reformist Qing prince who led foreign policy and the Tongzhi Restoration. He headed the Zongli Yamen and dealt with the foreign powers after 1860. His influence rose and fell with court politics around Cixi.",
"Sushun_(Qing_dynasty)": "A powerful Qing official purged in the 1861 coup that empowered Cixi. He had been a leading regent for the boy emperor Tongzhi. His fall cleared the way for Cixi's long ascendancy.",
"Auguste_Chapdelaine": "The French missionary whose 1856 execution gave France a pretext for the Second Opium War. He was put to death while preaching illegally in Guangxi. France used his killing to justify joining Britain against China.",
"Battle_of_Palikao": "The 1860 battle near Beijing where Anglo-French forces routed the Qing army. Modern firepower shattered the Qing cavalry charge. The victory opened the capital to the foreign expedition.",
"Coolie": "An indentured Chinese laborer, many shipped abroad under harsh conditions in this era. Thousands were sent overseas to work mines, plantations, and railways. The trade in their labor often resembled a form of bondage.",
"Ussuri_River": "The river marking part of the Manchurian border ceded to Russia in 1860. Flowing north into the Amur, it was fixed as the Sino-Russian boundary by the Convention of Peking. Its banks were the scene of a brief but tense border war between China and the Soviet Union in 1969.",
"Heilongjiang": "China's northernmost province, much of whose northern lands Russia annexed. Named after the Amur, or Black Dragon River, that forms its border with Russia, it is a cold region of forests and grain plains. Long part of the Manchu homeland, it later became a center of heavy industry and oil production.",
"Vladivostok": "The Russian Pacific port founded on territory taken from Qing China in 1860. Its name means 'ruler of the East', signaling Russia's ambitions on the Pacific, and it became the terminus of the Trans-Siberian Railway. The city anchored Russian power in the Far East and remains its chief Pacific naval base.",
"Catholic_Church": "The Roman Catholic mission whose protected status in China stirred anti-foreign feeling. Treaties after the Opium Wars guaranteed missionaries the right to preach and own property, and their interventions in local disputes bred resentment. Anti-Christian anger fed incidents such as the Tianjin Massacre and the Boxer Uprising.",
"Henan": "A populous central province on the Yellow River plain. One of the cradles of Chinese civilization, it contains ancient capitals such as Luoyang and Kaifeng. Densely farmed and often flooded, it suffered catastrophic famines, including the great famine of 1942.",
"Jiangsu": "The wealthy eastern province containing Nanjing and Shanghai's hinterland. Crossed by the Yangtze and the Grand Canal, it has long been one of China's richest and most commercial regions. Its cities of Nanjing, Suzhou, and Yangzhou were major centers of late-imperial culture.",
"Zhili": "The Qing capital province around Beijing, later renamed Hebei. Its name means 'directly ruled', reflecting its administration straight from the imperial court. As the seat of power it gave its name to the Zhili clique of warlords who dominated Beijing politics.",
"Wuchang_District": "The Wuhan district where the 1911 uprising against the Qing began. On October 10, 1911, mutinous New Army soldiers there seized the city, triggering the revolution that toppled the dynasty. The date is commemorated as Double Ten Day, the national day of the Republic of China.",
"Anqing": "The Anhui city and Taiping stronghold recaptured by Qing forces in 1861. Its fall to Zeng Guofan's Xiang Army was a turning point that opened the way to retaking Nanjing. The city later hosted one of China's first modern arsenals under the Self-Strengthening Movement.",
"Marble_Boat": "The ornate lakeside pavilion at the Summer Palace, emblem of Cixi's extravagance. Legend holds that funds meant for the modern navy were diverted to rebuild the Summer Palace, including this immovable stone boat. It became a symbol of the court's misplaced priorities on the eve of defeat by Japan.",
"Yingtai": "The islet in Beijing where the Guangxu Emperor was confined after 1898. After the failed Hundred Days' Reform, Empress Dowager Cixi placed the emperor under palace arrest on this lake island. He remained a virtual prisoner there until his death in 1908.",
"Arsenic_poisoning": "The means by which the Guangxu Emperor is now believed to have been killed in 1908. Forensic tests in 2008 found massive levels of arsenic in his remains, confirming he was poisoned a day before Cixi herself died. Suspicion has long fallen on Cixi or her allies, who feared the reformist emperor would reverse course once free.",
"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)": "A massive Muslim uprising in China's northwest, crushed by Zuo Zongtang. Sparked by ethnic and religious tension, it engulfed Shaanxi and Gansu, killing millions and devastating the region. Its suppression restored Qing control and paved the way for the reconquest of Xinjiang.",
"Grand_Council_(Qing_dynasty)": "The inner body of top officials that ran high policy for the Qing throne. Created under the Yongzheng Emperor, it bypassed older bureaucracies to give the emperor swift, secret control over state affairs. It remained the center of government until late-Qing reforms replaced it with a cabinet in 1911.",
"Vietnam": "The Southeast Asian land whose control China lost to France in the 1880s. A long-time tributary of the Chinese empire, it became the focus of the Sino-French War of 1884. China's defeat ended its suzerainty and confirmed French colonial rule over the territory.",
"Yung_Wing": "The first Chinese graduate of a US university, who led the Chinese Educational Mission. A Yale graduate of 1854, he persuaded the Qing to send young students to study in America in the 1870s. He devoted his life to reform, though the mission was recalled early amid official suspicion.",
"Kaiping_Mines": "A pioneering Self-Strengthening coal-mining enterprise in north China. Founded by Li Hongzhang in 1878, it supplied fuel for steamships and arsenals. It became one of the country's largest modern collieries before passing into foreign hands after the Boxer crisis.",
"Li–Lobanov_Treaty": "An 1896 secret Sino-Russian alliance allowing Russia to build a Manchurian railway. Negotiated by Li Hongzhang at the tsar's coronation, it aligned China with Russia against Japan and granted the Chinese Eastern Railway concession. It drew Russia deep into Manchuria and helped set the stage for the Russo-Japanese War.",
"Juren": "A provincial-level degree holder in the imperial examination system. Earned by passing the triennial provincial examinations, the rank qualified a man for office and exempted him from labor service. It stood above the entry-level shengyuan and below the metropolitan jinshi degree.",
"Zhejiang": "A prosperous eastern coastal province south of Shanghai. Wealthy from silk, tea, and maritime trade, it includes Hangzhou, Ningbo, and the port of Wenzhou. In modern times it became a heartland of private enterprise and export manufacturing.",
"Hui_people": "China's Chinese-speaking Muslim minority, involved in several 19th-century revolts. Descended from Arab, Persian, and Central Asian traders intermarried with Han Chinese, they are spread nationwide but concentrated in the northwest. They were central to the Dungan revolts and remain one of the largest recognized minorities.",
"Yaqub_Beg": "The adventurer who carved out a short-lived Muslim state in Xinjiang in the 1860s. A Kokandi military leader, he exploited the Dungan revolt to seize most of the Tarim Basin and won recognition from Britain and Russia. His state collapsed when Zuo Zongtang's armies reconquered Xinjiang in 1877.",
"Yettishar": "Yaqub Beg's breakaway Muslim state in Xinjiang, reconquered by the Qing in 1877. The name means 'seven cities', for the oasis towns of the Tarim Basin it controlled. Its fall led the Qing to reorganize the region as the province of Xinjiang in 1884.",
"Hu_Xueyan": "A famous Qing merchant-financier who backed Zuo Zongtang's campaigns. Rising from humble origins, he built a banking and trading empire and helped fund the reconquest of Xinjiang. His spectacular bankruptcy became a byword for the perils of mixing commerce and politics.",
"HSBC": "The Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation, the leading British bank in China. Founded in 1865 to finance the China trade, it arranged many of the Qing government's foreign loans and indemnity payments. It grew into one of the most powerful financial institutions in East Asia.",
"Ding_Ruchang": "The admiral who commanded the Beiyang Fleet and died after its defeat in 1895. A former cavalry officer, he led China's modern northern navy against Japan in the First Sino-Japanese War. Trapped at Weihaiwei, he took his own life rather than surrender, and the fleet was lost.",
"Protectorate": "A weaker state controlled by a stronger power, a status imposed across China's periphery. Under such arrangements a dominant nation directs the foreign affairs and often the internal rule of the protected territory. Foreign powers reduced several of China's tributary states to protectorates in the nineteenth century.",
"French_Indochina": "France's Southeast Asian colony, expanded at China's expense after the Sino-French War. It united Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos under French rule, ending China's traditional influence in the region. From there France pressed for railway and mining concessions in neighboring Yunnan.",
"Guangzhouwan": "A small territory near Canton leased to France in 1898. Part of the scramble for concessions, the lease gave France a foothold on the south China coast. It was administered from French Indochina until returned to China in 1945.",
"Open_Door_Policy": "The US-promoted principle (1899) of equal trade access to China for all powers. Articulated in notes by Secretary of State John Hay, it sought to keep China open to American commerce and prevent partition into exclusive spheres. It remained a touchstone of US China policy for the next four decades.",
"John_Hay": "The US Secretary of State who issued the Open Door notes on China. Serving under McKinley and Roosevelt, he sought to protect American commercial interests as the powers carved out spheres of influence. His notes also affirmed support for China's territorial integrity during the Boxer crisis.",
"Zhang_Xun": "The royalist general who briefly restored the Qing emperor in 1917. Known as the 'pigtailed general' for keeping the Manchu queue, he marched on Beijing and placed the boy emperor Puyi back on the throne. The restoration collapsed within days under attack from republican forces.",
"Nationalism": "Devotion to the nation, a defining force in modern Chinese politics. Galvanized by foreign aggression, it inspired both the anti-Manchu revolution and later campaigns against imperialism. It formed the first of Sun Yat-sen's Three Principles of the People.",
"Constitutionalism": "The movement for government limited by a written constitution, pressed in the late Qing. Reformers urged the throne to grant a constitution and parliament on the model of Meiji Japan. The Qing's slow, half-hearted concessions failed to satisfy demands and hastened the 1911 revolution.",
"United_States_Secretary_of_State": "The chief US foreign-affairs official, such as John Hay or George Marshall. The office heads the State Department and directs American diplomacy abroad. Several secretaries shaped US policy toward China, from the Open Door notes to the postwar mediation mission.",
"Washington_Naval_Conference": "The 1921 to 1922 talks that affirmed China's integrity and capped naval arms. The Nine-Power Treaty pledged respect for China's sovereignty and the Open Door, while other accords limited battleship fleets. It restrained Japanese expansion for a decade but lacked enforcement when Japan later moved on Manchuria.",
"Missionary": "A foreign religious worker whose protected presence often stoked anti-foreign anger. Thousands of Christian missionaries spread through China after the treaties of the 1860s, founding churches, schools, and hospitals. Their privileged legal status and conversions clashed with local society, helping spark the Boxer Uprising.",
"Edward_Hobart_Seymour": "The British admiral whose 1900 relief column was halted short of besieged Beijing. He led an allied force from Tianjin to rescue the legations but was driven back by Boxers and Qing troops. His failure underscored the gravity of the crisis and prompted a larger expedition.",
"Battle_of_the_Taku_Forts_(1900)": "The 1900 allied capture of the forts guarding Tianjin during the Boxer crisis. The forts commanded the river approach to Beijing, and their seizure by foreign warships pushed the Qing court toward declaring war. Their fall opened the path for the relief of the besieged capital.",
"Alfred_Gaselee": "The British general who led the allied force that relieved Beijing in 1900. He commanded the Eight-Nation Alliance column that fought its way from Tianjin to lift the siege of the legations. The relief ended fifty-five days of fighting and led to the punitive Boxer Protocol.",
"Siege_of_the_International_Legations": "The 55-day Boxer siege of the foreign legations in Beijing in 1900. Diplomats, guards, and Chinese Christians held out in the legation quarter while Boxers and imperial troops attacked. Their rescue by the Eight-Nation Alliance brought harsh reprisals and a crushing indemnity on China.",
"Boxer_Indemnity_Scholarship_Program": "A scheme funding Chinese students in the US from remitted Boxer indemnity money. The United States returned part of its indemnity to educate Chinese students in America, beginning in 1909. The program helped found Tsinghua University and trained a generation of reform-minded scholars.",
"Revive_China_Society": "Sun Yat-sen's first revolutionary society, founded in 1894. Established among overseas Chinese in Honolulu, it aimed to overthrow the Qing and was behind early failed uprisings. It later merged into the larger Tongmenghui, the forerunner of the Nationalist Party.",
"Huang_Xing": "A leading military organizer of the 1911 revolution, second only to Sun Yat-sen. He planned and led several armed uprisings and commanded revolutionary forces at the defense of Nanjing. Often paired with Sun as 'Sun-Huang', he died in 1916 shortly after the republic's troubled birth.",
"Overseas_Chinese": "Chinese communities abroad who funded and supported the republican revolution. Sun Yat-sen called them the mother of the revolution for the money and recruits they sent from Southeast Asia and the Americas. They remained an important source of investment and political support in the modern era.",
"Huanghuagang_Uprising": "A failed 1911 revolutionary revolt in Canton whose 72 martyrs became iconic. The attack on the governor-general's compound was crushed, but the dead were enshrined as heroes of the cause. The sacrifice galvanized opinion only months before the successful Wuchang Uprising.",
"Sun_Yat-sen_Mausoleum": "The grand Nanjing tomb of the republic's founding father, Sun Yat-sen. Built on Purple Mountain in the late 1920s, its monumental stairway and hall became a national shrine. It symbolized the Nationalist government's claim to Sun's revolutionary legacy.",
"Five-Power_Constitution": "Sun Yat-sen's scheme of government dividing power among five branches. It added traditional Chinese examination and control bodies to the Western executive, legislative, and judicial powers. The design shaped the structure of the Republic of China's government.",
"Socialism": "The doctrine of social ownership that influenced many Chinese reformers and revolutionaries. Ideas of common ownership and equality attracted intellectuals seeking alternatives to warlordism and capitalism. Sun Yat-sen's people's livelihood drew on socialist thought, which the Communists later carried furthest.",
"Constitution_of_the_Republic_of_China": "The fundamental law of the Republic of China, adopted in 1947. Promulgated by the Nationalist government, it established a republican framework based on Sun Yat-sen's principles. Suspended on the mainland during the civil war, it remains in force on Taiwan.",
"Double_Ten_Day": "October 10, the Republic of China's national day, marking the 1911 Wuchang Uprising. The date recalls the soldiers' mutiny that began the revolution against the Qing. It is still celebrated as the founding anniversary of the republic, especially on Taiwan.",
"Japanese_invasion_of_Manchuria": "Japan's 1931 seizure of Manchuria following the Mukden Incident. Using a staged railway bombing as a pretext, the Kwantung Army overran the northeast and created the puppet state of Manchukuo. The conquest exposed the weakness of the League of Nations and began Japan's wider aggression.",
"International_Military_Tribunal_for_the_Far_East": "The Tokyo trials that prosecuted Japanese leaders for wartime crimes. Sitting from 1946 to 1948, it tried senior officials for waging aggressive war and atrocities, including those in China. Several defendants were executed, though the emperor was spared prosecution.",
"Cai_E": "The general who led the 1915 revolt against Yuan Shikai's monarchy. From Yunnan he launched the National Protection War that rallied provinces against Yuan's bid to become emperor. His campaign helped force Yuan to abandon the throne, though Cai died soon after of illness.",
"Anhui_clique": "The warlord faction led by Duan Qirui after Yuan Shikai's death. Backed by Japanese loans, it dominated the Beijing government in the late 1910s. Its defeat in the 1920 Zhili–Anhui War broke its hold on power.",
"Zhili–Anhui_War": "The 1920 war in which the Zhili clique defeated the Anhui clique. The brief conflict around Beijing toppled Duan Qirui's dominance and left the Zhili faction in control of the capital. It was an early round in the cycle of warlord wars that fragmented China.",
"Constitutional_Protection_Movement": "Sun Yat-sen's campaigns from Canton to defend the republican constitution. After northern warlords dissolved parliament, Sun set up a rival southern government to restore the 1912 constitution. The movement's repeated failures convinced him to rebuild on Soviet help and a party army.",
"Yan_Xishan": "The long-ruling 'model governor' warlord of Shanxi province. He controlled Shanxi for decades, promoting industry and order while shifting alliances to survive. He eventually joined the Nationalist government and followed it to Taiwan after 1949.",
"Liaoning": "A southern Manchurian province centered on Shenyang, formerly Mukden. The most industrialized part of the northeast, it held rich coal and iron and the railway zone coveted by Japan. It became a cornerstone of heavy industry under the People's Republic.",
"Generalissimo": "The supreme military title held by Chiang Kai-shek as Nationalist leader. The rank marked him as commander-in-chief of all China's armed forces during the war with Japan. Western media made 'the Generalissimo' a familiar name for Chiang during World War II.",
"Shenyang": "The major Manchurian city, known as Mukden, site of the 1931 incident. The largest city of the northeast and a former Qing capital, it commanded the region's railways and industry. The staged explosion on its outskirts gave Japan the pretext to invade Manchuria.",
"Qian_Xuantong": "A New Culture scholar known for radical proposals to reform the Chinese language. A linguist and editor of New Youth, he even suggested abolishing Chinese characters in favor of an alphabet. His provocations dramatized the movement's drive to modernize Chinese writing.",
"Science": "One of the twin ideals, with democracy, championed by the New Culture Movement. Personified as 'Mr Science', it stood for reason, empirical inquiry, and the rejection of superstition. Together with 'Mr Democracy' it defined the reformist agenda of the 1910s and 1920s.",
"Filial_piety": "The Confucian duty of devotion to parents, attacked by New Culture radicals. Long the cornerstone of Chinese family ethics, it demanded obedience and care toward elders and ancestors. Reformers blamed it for stifling the individual and propping up an oppressive old order.",
"Arranged_marriage": "The traditional family-arranged marriage criticized by New Culture reformers. Matches were settled by parents and matchmakers, often without the couple's consent, to serve family interests. The May Fourth generation championed free-choice marriage as a symbol of personal liberation.",
"A_Madman's_Diary": "Lu Xun's landmark 1918 story attacking the 'cannibalism' of old Chinese society. Written in vernacular Chinese, it uses a paranoid narrator to indict the Confucian tradition as devouring its people. It is regarded as the first major work of modern Chinese literature.",
"Liberalism": "The political philosophy of individual rights and freedoms, advanced by figures like Hu Shih. It stressed constitutional government, free inquiry, and gradual reform over revolution. Squeezed between Nationalist authoritarianism and Communist revolution, it struggled to find a foothold in China.",
"John_Dewey": "The American philosopher whose 1919 China lectures spread pragmatism and progressive education. Hosted by former students like Hu Shih, he toured the country urging experimental, child-centered schooling and democratic reform. His ideas shaped Chinese educators even as more radical doctrines gained ground.",
"Bolsheviks": "Lenin's revolutionary faction whose 1917 victory inspired China's communists. Their seizure of power in Russia showed that a disciplined Marxist party could overturn an old regime. Their success and Comintern support directly encouraged the founding of the Chinese Communist Party in 1921.",
"Hebei": "The northern province surrounding Beijing, formerly called Zhili. Renamed in 1928 when the capital moved to Nanjing, it encircles both Beijing and Tianjin. Its position made it a strategic prize in the warlord wars and the resistance against Japan.",
"Peasant": "The rural farming majority that Mao made the base of his revolution. Breaking with orthodox Marxism's focus on urban workers, Mao saw China's vast peasantry as the engine of revolt. Land reform and peasant mobilization became central to the Communist rise to power.",
"Kunming": "The Yunnan capital that sheltered wartime universities and anchored the Burma Road. Far from the Japanese front, it hosted the famed National Southwestern Associated University and a hub of Allied supply. It was the Chinese terminus of the Burma Road and the airlift over the Himalayan 'Hump'.",
"Leninism": "Lenin's theory of a disciplined vanguard party, adopted by both the KMT and the CCP. It called for a tightly organized party leading the masses through democratic centralism toward revolution. Soviet advisers reorganized the Nationalists along Leninist lines in the 1920s, and the Communists embraced it fully.",
"Guangzhou_Uprising": "A failed 1927 Communist revolt that briefly held Canton. Communist forces seized parts of the city and proclaimed a commune, but Nationalist troops crushed it within days. The bloody defeat capped a year of disasters for the party after its split with the Nationalists.",
"Martial_law_in_Taiwan": "The decades of military rule the Nationalists imposed on Taiwan until 1987. Declared in 1949, it banned opposition and underpinned the long White Terror against dissent. Its lifting opened the way to Taiwan's democratization.",
"Lee_Teng-hui": "Taiwan's president from 1988 to 2000 who led its transition to democracy. The first native-born Taiwanese leader, he oversaw free elections, including the first direct presidential vote in 1996. Beijing denounced his moves toward a distinct Taiwanese identity.",
"Democratic_Progressive_Party": "Taiwan's main opposition party, founded in 1986 and favoring Taiwanese identity. It emerged from the dangwai movement against one-party Nationalist rule and won the presidency in 2000. It generally leans toward Taiwanese self-determination and away from unification with the mainland.",
"Franklin_D._Roosevelt": "The US president whose wartime alliance treated China as a great power. He backed Chiang's government with aid and insisted China be counted among the Big Four Allies. His vision of a strong, friendly China underpinned its seat on the future UN Security Council.",
"Joseph_Stilwell": "The American general and Chiang's chief of staff, whose feuds with him hampered the war. Nicknamed 'Vinegar Joe', he pushed to reform China's armies and reopen the Burma supply route. His bitter clashes with Chiang led to his recall in 1944.",
"Fabi": "The Nationalist paper currency introduced in 1935, later ruined by hyperinflation. The reform pooled silver and put China on a managed paper money to stabilize finance. Wartime deficits and reckless printing destroyed its value, helping doom the Nationalist regime.",
"Silver_standard": "The silver-based monetary system China used until its 1935 currency reform. For centuries Chinese money rested on silver by weight, leaving it exposed to swings in the world silver price. American silver-buying in the 1930s drained China's reserves and forced the shift to paper currency.",
"T._V._Soong": "The Western-educated financier and Chiang in-law who managed Nationalist finances. A Harvard graduate and brother of Madame Chiang, he served as finance minister and premier and reorganized the banking system. He was a key link to the United States and one of the era's most powerful figures.",
"Sino-German_cooperation_(1926–1941)": "The interwar partnership in which Germany modernized Chiang's army and industry. German advisers trained elite Nationalist divisions and helped build arsenals in exchange for Chinese raw materials. The collaboration ended once Nazi Germany chose alliance with Japan.",
"Hyperinflation": "The runaway price spiral that destroyed Nationalist finances in the late 1940s. Vast deficits and unrestrained money printing sent prices doubling within days by 1948. The economic collapse shattered public confidence and sped the Communist victory.",
"Nanchang": "The Jiangxi capital where the Communists launched their 1927 uprising. On August 1, Communist officers led a mutiny there in the first armed revolt against the Nationalists. The date is marked as the founding of the People's Liberation Army.",
"Nazi_Germany": "Hitler's Germany, which advised Chiang's army before switching to ally with Japan. Through the mid-1930s German officers and arms upgraded China's military under the Sino-German partnership. Berlin abandoned the relationship in 1938 in favor of the Anti-Comintern Pact with Tokyo.",
"Fifth_Encirclement_Campaign": "The 1934 Nationalist offensive that forced the Communists onto the Long March. Advised by German strategists, Chiang ringed the Jiangxi Soviet with blockhouses and slowly strangled it. The Communists broke out and began the epic retreat that remade their leadership under Mao.",
"Peng_Dehuai": "A top Red Army commander in the war with Japan and the civil war. He led the Hundred Regiments Offensive against the Japanese and later Chinese forces in the Korean War. His criticism of the Great Leap Forward led to his purge in 1959.",
"Comintern": "The Soviet-led Communist International that directed and advised the Chinese party. Founded in 1919, it sent agents and funds and dictated strategy, including the early alliance with the Nationalists. Its often ill-fitting orders contributed to Communist setbacks before Mao charted a more independent course.",
"Edgar_Snow": "The American journalist whose reporting introduced Mao and the Communists to the West. In 1936 he became the first Western reporter to visit the Communist base and interview Mao at length. His sympathetic account shaped foreign perceptions of the Chinese revolution.",
"Red_Star_Over_China": "Edgar Snow's 1937 book that sympathetically portrayed Mao's Communists. Based on his visit to the wartime base, it presented them as disciplined patriots and reformers. The book won them admirers abroad and among Chinese youth.",
"7th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party": "The 1945 congress that enshrined Mao Zedong Thought as party doctrine. Held in Yan'an, it confirmed Mao's supremacy and unified the party on the eve of victory. Its decisions set the ideological framework for the People's Republic.",
"Lytton_Report": "The League of Nations inquiry that condemned Japan's 1931 seizure of Manchuria. It found Japan the aggressor and refused to recognize the puppet state of Manchukuo. Rather than comply, Japan walked out of the League in 1933.",
"Hirohito": "The emperor of Japan throughout its wartime expansion and 1945 surrender. He reigned as Japan invaded China and the Pacific, then announced the surrender by radio in August 1945. Allowed to keep his throne under US occupation, his wartime role remains debated.",
"Puppet_state": "A nominally independent regime controlled by a foreign power, as Manchukuo was by Japan. Such states keep the forms of sovereignty while their masters dictate policy and station troops. Japan created several in occupied China to legitimize and administer its conquests.",
"Unit_731": "The covert Japanese army unit that conducted lethal biological-warfare experiments in Manchuria. Based near Harbin, it killed thousands of prisoners through disease, vivisection, and frostbite tests. Many of its leaders escaped prosecution in exchange for handing their data to the United States.",
"Yang_Hucheng": "The general who, with Zhang Xueliang, seized Chiang in the 1936 Xi'an Incident. The two commanders detained Chiang to force him to halt the civil war and unite against Japan. Yang was later imprisoned for years and executed on Chiang's orders in 1949.",
"Imperial_Japanese_Army": "The army of imperial Japan that invaded and occupied much of China. Its Kwantung Army engineered the conquest of Manchuria, and it spearheaded the full-scale war from 1937. Its brutal campaigns, including the Nanjing Massacre, defined the suffering of wartime China.",
"Burma_Road": "The mountain supply route that carried Allied aid to wartime China. Built by hand through rugged terrain, it linked Burma to Kunming and was China's lifeline after its ports fell. When Japan cut it in 1942, supplies had to be flown over the Himalayan 'Hump'.",
"Patrick_J._Hurley": "The US envoy who brokered the failed 1945 Chongqing talks between Chiang and Mao. As ambassador he flew Mao to meet Chiang and pushed for a unified government. The talks produced an agreement that quickly collapsed, and his mission ended in frustration.",
"Coalition_government": "A power-sharing government, proposed but never realized between the KMT and CCP. American mediators urged the rivals to merge their forces and form a joint administration after the war. Mutual distrust doomed the idea and the country slid into full civil war.",
"Double_Tenth_Agreement": "The October 1945 accord from the Chongqing talks that quickly broke down. Signed by the Nationalists and Communists, it pledged to avoid civil war and convene a political conference. Fighting resumed within months as both sides maneuvered for advantage.",
"Political_Consultative_Conference": "The 1946 multiparty conference that failed to avert the civil war. Convened in Chongqing with American backing, it brought together Nationalists, Communists, and minor parties to plan a constitutional government. Its resolutions unraveled as fighting spread, and full-scale war followed."
};

/* ============================================================
   Supplementary glossary entries — curated descriptions for the
   most frequently referenced terms that previously fell back to a
   generic placeholder, plus a table of start/end dates rendered
   beside the title. Appended after the main GLOSSARY above.
   ============================================================ */
Object.assign(window.GLOSSARY, {
  // ----- dynasties & periods -----
  "Han_dynasty": "The dynasty (202 BCE–220 CE) that consolidated the imperial system begun by the Qin and gave the Chinese majority its name. Under emperors such as Wu it pushed into Central Asia, opened the Silk Road, and made Confucianism the basis of statecraft. So formative was its model of bureaucratic empire that later ages looked back on the Han as a golden age.",
  "Song_dynasty": "The dynasty (960–1279) that reunified China after the Five Dynasties and presided over a commercial, technological, and cultural flowering. It saw paper money, gunpowder weapons, printing, and a refined examination system, but lost the north to the Jin in 1127 and finally fell to the Mongols. Its Neo-Confucian thinkers reshaped Chinese philosophy for centuries.",
  "Yuan_dynasty": "The Mongol-led dynasty (1271–1368) founded by Kublai Khan, ruling China as part of the wider Mongol Empire. It made Beijing the capital and reopened trade across Eurasia, hosting travellers such as Marco Polo, while treating Han Chinese as a subordinate class. Misrule, inflation, and disasters bred the rebellions that brought in the Ming.",
  "Qin_dynasty": "China's first unified imperial dynasty (221–206 BCE), forged by Qin Shi Huang from the warring states. It standardized script, weights, currency, and law along Legalist lines and began the Great Wall, but its harshness made it short-lived. Its centralized administrative model became the template for two millennia of imperial rule.",
  "Zhou_dynasty": "The longest-lasting Chinese dynasty (c. 1046–256 BCE), which overthrew the Shang and introduced the doctrine of the Mandate of Heaven. Its later centuries fragmented into the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods, an age of warfare that nonetheless produced Confucius and the Hundred Schools of Thought. The Zhou are remembered as the cultural bedrock of Chinese civilization.",
  "Shang_dynasty": "The earliest Chinese dynasty confirmed by archaeology (c. 1600–1046 BCE), centred on the Yellow River. It is known for ritual bronzes, a society of kings and diviners, and the oracle-bone inscriptions that are the oldest Chinese writing. It was overthrown by the Zhou, who cast its last rulers as tyrants.",
  "Sui_dynasty": "The short but pivotal dynasty (581–618) that reunified China after centuries of division. It rebuilt central institutions, dug the Grand Canal linking north and south, and revived the examinations, but ruinous wars and forced labour provoked revolt. Its reforms were inherited and perfected by the Tang.",
  "Liao_dynasty": "The dynasty (916–1125) founded by the nomadic Khitan in the north, ruling Mongolia, Manchuria, and part of northern China alongside the Song. It governed its steppe and Chinese subjects through a dual administration and devised its own script. It was destroyed by the Jurchen, who founded the Jin.",
  "Three_Kingdoms": "The era (220–280) of division after the Han, when the rival states of Wei, Shu, and Wu contended for control. Its battles and heroes were later immortalized in the novel Romance of the Three Kingdoms. The period ended when the Jin briefly reunified the realm.",
  "Spring_and_Autumn_period": "The first half of the Eastern Zhou (770–476 BCE), when royal authority decayed and the feudal states grew increasingly independent. It saw constant diplomacy and warfare among dozens of polities and the life of Confucius. It takes its name from a chronicle traditionally linked to him.",
  "Warring_States_period": "The era (475–221 BCE) of intensifying conflict among seven major states that ended the Zhou order. It brought mass infantry armies, iron weapons, and sweeping reforms, and was the great age of Chinese philosophy. It closed when Qin conquered its rivals and unified China.",
  "Mongol_Empire": "The largest contiguous land empire in history, founded by Genghis Khan in 1206 and spanning Asia to Eastern Europe. Its conquests linked Eurasia in trade and exchange but were achieved through devastating campaigns. In China its rulers established the Yuan dynasty under Kublai Khan.",
  "Qin_(state)": "One of the seven Warring States, holding the strategic northwest of China. Strengthened by the Legalist reforms of Shang Yang, it built a powerful army and centralized bureaucracy. Under its king Ying Zheng it conquered the other states to found the Qin dynasty.",
  "Chu_(state)": "A large southern state of the Zhou era, centred on the middle Yangtze. Long viewed as half-barbarian by the northern states, it grew into one of the mightiest Warring States and a centre of distinctive art and poetry. It was among the last great rivals conquered by Qin.",

  // ----- figures: ancient & imperial -----
  "Confucius": "The teacher and philosopher (551–479 BCE) whose ideas became the ethical foundation of Chinese civilization. He taught that social harmony rests on virtue, ritual propriety, and proper relationships rather than force. His sayings, gathered in the Analects, shaped governance and education across East Asia for two thousand years.",
  "Mencius": "The Confucian philosopher (c. 372–289 BCE) regarded as the tradition's greatest thinker after Confucius. He argued that human nature is innately good and that rulers govern legitimately only by caring for the people. His writings became one of the Four Books central to later study.",
  "Laozi": "The semi-legendary sage traditionally credited with founding Daoism and writing the Daodejing. He is said to have taught the way of effortless action and harmony with the natural order. Whether he was a single historical person remains uncertain.",
  "Sima_Qian": "The Han historian (c. 145–86 BCE) regarded as the father of Chinese historiography. His Records of the Grand Historian set the form for the official histories of every later dynasty. He famously chose mutilation over death in order to finish his work.",
  "Qin_Shi_Huang": "The king of Qin who unified China and became its first emperor, reigning as emperor from 221 to 210 BCE. He standardized writing, measures, and law, began the Great Wall, and built a vast tomb guarded by the Terracotta Army. His rule was mighty but harsh, and his dynasty collapsed soon after his death.",
  "Emperor_Wu_of_Han": "The Han emperor (reigned 141–87 BCE) under whom the dynasty reached its height. He expanded the empire deep into Central Asia and the south, opened the Silk Road, and made Confucianism state orthodoxy. His long wars strained the treasury but greatly enlarged Chinese power.",
  "Kublai_Khan": "The Mongol ruler (1215–1294) who completed the conquest of China and founded the Yuan dynasty. Grandson of Genghis Khan, he moved his capital to Beijing and ruled as a Chinese emperor over a Eurasian empire. His court was described to Europe by Marco Polo.",
  "Marco_Polo": "The Venetian merchant (1254–1324) whose account of his travels brought Yuan China to European readers. He claimed to have served the court of Kublai Khan for many years before returning home. His book shaped Western images of Asia for centuries.",
  "Xuanzang": "The Tang Buddhist monk (c. 602–664) who made a seventeen-year pilgrimage to India for scriptures. He brought back hundreds of texts and devoted his life to translating them, deepening Chinese Buddhism. His journey later inspired the classic novel Journey to the West.",
  "Li_Bai": "One of the greatest poets of the Tang dynasty (701–762), famed for his romantic, exuberant verse. His poems on wine, friendship, nature, and the moon are among the best loved in Chinese. He is often paired with Du Fu as a twin peak of Chinese poetry.",
  "Zhu_Xi": "The Song philosopher (1130–1200) who synthesized Neo-Confucianism into the orthodox system of later imperial China. He selected and annotated the Four Books, which became the core of the examinations. His reading of Confucian thought dominated Chinese learning into the twentieth century.",
  "Hongwu_Emperor": "The founder of the Ming dynasty (reigned 1368–1398), born a peasant who rose through rebellion to expel the Mongols. He rebuilt a centralized, agrarian empire, ruling with autocratic severity and sweeping purges. He set institutions that shaped the Ming for nearly three centuries.",
  "Yongle_Emperor": "The third Ming emperor (reigned 1402–1424), who seized the throne from his nephew. He moved the capital to Beijing, built the Forbidden City, and sent Zheng He's treasure fleets across the Indian Ocean. His reign marked a high point of Ming power and prestige.",

  // ----- figures: modern -----
  "Xi_Jinping": "The paramount leader of China since 2012, serving as General Secretary of the Communist Party, state president, and head of the military. He has centralized authority, waged a sweeping anti-corruption campaign, and enshrined his own doctrine in the party charter. In 2018 presidential term limits were removed, ending the post-Mao pattern of fixed-term succession.",
  "Jiang_Zemin": "China's paramount leader from 1989 to 2002, who became party chief after the Tiananmen crackdown. He presided over rapid growth, entry into the World Trade Organization, and the return of Hong Kong. His doctrine, the 'Three Represents,' opened the party to entrepreneurs.",
  "Hu_Jintao": "China's paramount leader from 2002 to 2012, known for a cautious, consensus style. His era stressed a 'harmonious society' and 'scientific development' amid breakneck growth and rising inequality. He oversaw the 2008 Beijing Olympics and China's rise to the world's second-largest economy.",
  "Hua_Guofeng": "Mao Zedong's chosen successor, who led China briefly from 1976 to 1978. He arrested the Gang of Four to end the Cultural Revolution but clung to Maoist orthodoxy. He was soon outmaneuvered by Deng Xiaoping and eased from power.",
  "Liu_Shaoqi": "A senior Communist leader and head of state once designated as Mao Zedong's successor. A pragmatic administrator, he helped China recover from the Great Leap Forward famine. Branded a traitor during the Cultural Revolution, he was purged and died in detention, later officially rehabilitated.",
  "Zhao_Ziyang": "A reformist premier and party general secretary in the 1980s associated with economic liberalization. He was purged in 1989 for sympathizing with the Tiananmen protesters and spent his last years under house arrest. His fall ended the most open phase of post-Mao reform.",
  "Chen_Yun": "A leading economic planner and one of the party's most powerful elders. He favoured cautious, state-guided reform, likening the market to a bird that must stay within the cage of the plan. He was a key conservative counterweight to Deng Xiaoping's bolder liberalization.",
  "Zhu_Rongji": "China's premier from 1998 to 2003, a blunt, reform-minded technocrat. He restructured bloated state enterprises, curbed inflation, overhauled the banks, and steered China into the World Trade Organization. He is remembered for his tough anti-corruption style.",
  "Li_Peng": "China's premier from 1987 to 1998, a Soviet-trained engineer and conservative. He is most associated with declaring martial law during the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests. He later championed major projects such as the Three Gorges Dam.",
  "Hu_Yaobang": "A reformist party leader of the 1980s known for liberal, humane policies. Forced to resign in 1987 for tolerating dissent, his death in April 1989 sparked the demonstrations that became the Tiananmen Square protests.",
  "Jiang_Qing": "Mao Zedong's last wife and a radical leader of the Cultural Revolution. As a member of the Gang of Four she wielded great power over culture and politics in the early 1970s. She was arrested after Mao's death, convicted, and died in 1991.",

  // ----- thought, classics & culture -----
  "Taoism": "A native Chinese philosophical and religious tradition centred on the Dao, the underlying way of the cosmos. Its classics, the Daodejing and Zhuangzi, prize spontaneity, simplicity, and harmony with nature over striving and rigid convention. As a religion it later developed gods, alchemy, and quests for immortality.",
  "Buddhism": "A religion and philosophy from ancient India that reached China along the Silk Road around the first century CE. It teaches release from suffering through ethical conduct, meditation, and insight into impermanence. Adapting to Chinese culture, it produced schools such as Chan (Zen) and became one of the country's three great traditions.",
  "Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)": "A hard-headed school of Chinese political thought that triumphed under the Qin. It held that order depends on strict laws, rewards, and punishments rather than virtue, and on concentrating power in the ruler. Officially condemned by later Confucians, its administrative methods nonetheless endured in imperial government.",
  "Neo-Confucianism": "A revival and reinterpretation of Confucian thought that took shape in the Song dynasty. Drawing on Buddhist and Daoist ideas, thinkers such as Zhu Xi developed a metaphysics of principle and material force underlying all things. It became the orthodox philosophy and examination curriculum of late imperial China.",
  "Yin_and_yang": "A foundational concept in Chinese thought describing complementary opposites whose interplay generates all phenomena. Yin is linked with the dark, yielding, and receptive, yang with the bright, active, and assertive, each holding a seed of the other. The idea underpins Chinese medicine, cosmology, and philosophy.",
  "Qi": "In Chinese thought, the vital energy or breath that animates and connects all things. Its flow and balance are central to traditional medicine, martial arts, and practices such as qigong and acupuncture. The term also names the material force underlying the cosmos in Chinese philosophy.",
  "Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)": "The Chinese theory of the Five Phases — wood, fire, earth, metal, and water — through which things arise and transform. The phases generate and overcome one another in fixed cycles used to explain nature, the body, and politics. The system pervades Chinese medicine, divination, and cosmology.",
  "Fengjian": "The decentralized order of the early Zhou, often rendered as Chinese feudalism. The king granted lands and titles to kin and allies who ruled their domains in return for loyalty and military service. Its breakdown produced the warfare of the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods.",
  "Hundred_Schools_of_Thought": "The flowering of competing philosophies during the late Zhou, roughly the sixth to third centuries BCE. Confucianism, Daoism, Legalism, Mohism, and others debated ethics, government, and the cosmos. This ferment laid the foundations of Chinese thought.",
  "Four_Books_and_Five_Classics": "The canonical texts of Confucianism that formed the core of Chinese education and the civil-service examinations. The Four Books were singled out by Zhu Xi as primers, while the older Five Classics gather works on poetry, history, ritual, divination, and chronicle. Mastery of them was the path to office in imperial China.",
  "Analects": "The collection of sayings and conversations of Confucius compiled by his disciples. It conveys his teachings on virtue, learning, ritual, and good government through brief, aphoristic passages. It is among the most influential books in Chinese history and one of the Four Books.",
  "Records_of_the_Grand_Historian": "The monumental history of China written by Sima Qian under the Han, reaching from the legendary Yellow Emperor to his own day. Organized into annals, biographies, and treatises, it set the form for all later dynastic histories. It is prized as both a historical source and a literary masterpiece.",
  "Chinese_characters": "The logographic script used to write Chinese for over three thousand years, in which each character stands for a word or part of one. Evolving from Shang oracle bones, it unified a linguistically diverse civilization and spread to Korea, Japan, and Vietnam. Tens of thousands exist, though a few thousand suffice for literacy.",
  "Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars": "A notorious suppression of dissent under Qin Shi Huang around 213–212 BCE. Texts outside approved subjects were ordered destroyed and, by later accounts, scholars who defied the regime were killed. The episode became a byword for tyranny over thought.",

  // ----- events & groups -----
  "Great_Leap_Forward": "Mao Zedong's campaign of 1958–1962 to turn China into a socialist industrial power almost overnight. Through mass communes and backyard furnaces it sought to leap past gradual development, but it shattered agriculture and falsified output. The result was history's deadliest famine, killing tens of millions.",
  "1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre": "Mass demonstrations in 1989, centred on Beijing's Tiananmen Square, demanding political reform and an end to corruption. After weeks of protest the government declared martial law and used the army to clear the square, killing many. The crackdown reshaped Chinese politics and drew lasting international condemnation.",
  "Anti-Rightist_Campaign": "A political purge launched in 1957 against intellectuals and others who had criticized the Communist Party. Hundreds of thousands were branded 'rightists,' losing their posts and sent for re-education or labour. It silenced dissent and foreshadowed harsher campaigns to come.",
  "Sino-Soviet_split": "The breakdown of the alliance between Communist China and the Soviet Union from the late 1950s. Ideological rivalry, competition to lead world communism, and clashing interests led to a full rupture and border clashes in 1969. The split eventually pushed China toward rapprochement with the United States.",
  "Gang_of_Four": "A radical faction led by Mao Zedong's wife Jiang Qing that dominated the late Cultural Revolution. Its members drove the era's most extreme policies and persecutions. They were arrested weeks after Mao's death in 1976 and blamed for the period's chaos.",
  "Boluan_Fanzheng": "The period after the Cultural Revolution, beginning in the late 1970s, in which Deng Xiaoping's leadership set out to 'eliminate chaos and return to normal.' Verdicts on the persecuted were reversed, the examinations and universities restored, and pragmatic policies revived. It cleared the ground for the reform era.",
  "China–United_States_trade_war": "The economic conflict between the world's two largest economies that escalated from 2018 with waves of tariffs. It grew out of disputes over the trade deficit, technology transfer, and industrial policy. It strained global supply chains and sharpened broader strategic rivalry.",

  // ----- places -----
  "Luoyang": "An ancient city in central China that served as capital under many dynasties, including the Eastern Zhou, Han, and Tang. Long a political and cultural heart of the country, it was a centre of early Buddhism near the Longmen Grottoes. It remains one of China's most historic cities.",
  "Chang'an": "The capital of several dynasties, most famously the Han and Tang, on the site of modern Xi'an. At its Tang height it was among the largest, most cosmopolitan cities in the world and the eastern terminus of the Silk Road. It symbolized the splendour of imperial China.",
  "Hangzhou": "A historic city on China's east coast, capital of the Southern Song and long famed for its beauty around West Lake. Marco Polo described it as among the finest cities on earth. Today it is a prosperous regional centre and home to firms such as Alibaba.",
  "Kaifeng": "A city in central China that was the bustling capital of the Northern Song. A hub of commerce along the Grand Canal, its life was captured in the scroll 'Along the River During the Qingming Festival.' Repeated flooding by the Yellow River later diminished it.",
  "Shenzhen": "A city in southern China bordering Hong Kong that became the showcase of Deng Xiaoping's reforms. Designated a Special Economic Zone in 1980, it grew from a small town into a technology megacity within a generation. It stands as a symbol of China's economic transformation.",
  "Great_Wall_of_China": "A vast system of fortifications built and rebuilt across northern China to guard against steppe invaders. Begun in earnest under the Qin and most elaborately constructed under the Ming, it runs for thousands of kilometres. It is the most famous symbol of China.",
  "Tiananmen_Square": "The monumental public square at the centre of Beijing, fronting the Forbidden City. It has been the stage for pivotal moments in modern Chinese history, from the May Fourth Movement to the founding of the People's Republic and the 1989 protests. It remains the symbolic heart of the state.",
  "Tarim_Basin": "A vast arid basin in northwest China, ringed by mountains and holding the Taklamakan Desert. Its oasis towns were key stops on the Silk Road linking China with Central Asia. It forms much of present-day Xinjiang.",
  "Gobi_Desert": "A great cold desert spanning northern China and southern Mongolia. It long formed a natural frontier between Chinese agrarian society and the nomads of the steppe. Caravans crossed it along branches of the Silk Road.",
  "Tibetan_Plateau": "The highest and largest plateau on earth, often called the roof of the world, lying in western China. Its melting glaciers feed many of Asia's great rivers. It is the homeland of Tibetan culture and a region of strategic importance.",
  "North_China_Plain": "The broad, fertile lowland built up by the Yellow River, the historic heartland of Chinese civilization. Its dense farming population made it the demographic and political core of the country. It remains one of the most heavily populated regions on earth.",
  "Pearl_River_Delta": "The densely urbanized delta in southern China around Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Hong Kong, and Macau. Opened first to reform, it became one of the world's great manufacturing and export hubs. It is among China's most prosperous regions.",
  "Inner_Mongolia": "An autonomous region along China's northern frontier, bordering the country of Mongolia. Historically a homeland of nomadic peoples, it is now mostly Han Chinese and rich in coal and rare earths. It blends grassland herding with heavy industry.",
  "Suzhou": "A historic city near Shanghai famed for its canals, classical gardens, and silk. A centre of culture and commerce since the Song, it was long a byword for refinement and wealth. Today it pairs its heritage with a major manufacturing economy.",
  "Chengdu": "The capital of Sichuan province in southwestern China, set in a fertile basin. A regional centre since antiquity, it is known for its relaxed culture, spicy cuisine, and giant pandas. It is one of western China's leading economic hubs.",
  "Qinghai": "A large, sparsely populated province on the northeastern Tibetan Plateau. It contains the sources of the Yellow and Yangtze rivers and China's largest lake. It is home to Tibetan, Hui, and other peoples.",

  // ----- economy, state & institutions -----
  "Chinese_economic_reform": "The sweeping program of market reforms launched under Deng Xiaoping from 1978 that transformed China's economy. It decollectivized farming, opened the country to foreign trade and investment, and allowed private enterprise alongside state control. Over four decades it lifted hundreds of millions out of poverty and made China a global power.",
  "Economy_of_China": "The world's second-largest economy by nominal output and the largest by purchasing power. Once centrally planned, it became a state-guided market economy after 1978, growing for decades as the 'world's factory.' It now faces challenges of debt, demographics, and the shift toward consumption and technology.",
  "Renminbi": "The official currency of the People's Republic of China, whose basic unit is the yuan. Issued by the People's Bank of China, it was long tightly managed against the US dollar and remains subject to capital controls. China has gradually promoted its use in international trade.",
  "Silk_Road": "The network of trade routes that linked China with Central Asia, the Middle East, and Europe from antiquity. Along it travelled silk and other goods as well as religions, technologies, and ideas such as Buddhism. It flourished especially under the Han and Tang and lends its name to modern initiatives.",
  "Planned_economy": "An economic system in which the state, rather than markets, directs production and allocation through central plans. China followed the Soviet model after 1949, setting output targets and fixing prices. Its inefficiencies prompted the market reforms begun in 1978.",
  "Socialist_market_economy": "China's official model since the 1990s, combining public ownership of key sectors with market mechanisms. It allows private business, competition, and prices to operate within a system the party still steers. The term frames China's hybrid of capitalism and state control.",
  "Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics": "The guiding ideology of the reform-era Communist Party, justifying market policies within a socialist framework. Coined under Deng Xiaoping, it holds that China must develop its economy through means suited to its own conditions. It has been periodically updated by later leaders.",
  "Special_economic_zones_of_China": "Coastal areas, beginning with Shenzhen in 1980, granted special freedoms to attract foreign investment and trade. With looser rules and tax incentives, they served as laboratories for market reform. Their success encouraged the wider opening of the economy.",
  "State-owned_enterprises_of_China": "Companies owned by the Chinese state that dominate strategic sectors such as energy, banking, and telecommunications. Once the whole of industry, many were restructured or closed in the reform era, but the largest remain pillars of the economy. They blend commercial aims with state direction.",
  "Five-year_plans_of_China": "The series of national development blueprints that have guided China's economy since 1953, modelled on Soviet planning. They set priorities and targets for growth and investment, evolving from rigid quotas toward broad strategy in the reform era. They remain a central tool of state policy.",
  "People's_commune": "The huge collective units that organized rural China during the Great Leap Forward and after. Communes pooled land, labour, and even households into a single system of work and welfare. They were dismantled in the early 1980s as farming returned to family households.",
  "Deng_Xiaoping_Theory": "The body of ideas associated with Deng Xiaoping that underpinned China's reform and opening. It stressed pragmatism, economic development, and 'socialism with Chinese characteristics' over ideological purity. It was written into the party constitution as official doctrine.",
  "Xi_Jinping_Thought": "The political doctrine associated with Xi Jinping, enshrined in the party and state constitutions. It calls for strengthened party leadership, national rejuvenation, and China's growing role in the world. Its elevation placed Xi alongside Mao and Deng in the party's ideological canon.",
  "Belt_and_Road_Initiative": "A vast Chinese infrastructure and investment program launched in 2013 to link China with Asia, Africa, and Europe. It funds ports, railways, and roads across dozens of countries, extending China's economic reach. Supporters see development; critics warn of debt and strategic leverage.",
  "Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping": "A sweeping drive launched after 2012 to punish official graft, targeting both 'tigers' and 'flies.' It has disciplined millions of officials and removed several senior rivals. It has bolstered Xi Jinping's authority while tightening party control.",
  "One-party_state": "A political system in which a single party holds a monopoly on power and other parties are barred or subordinate. In China the Communist Party has ruled without rival since 1949. It controls the government, military, and key institutions.",
  "Cult_of_personality": "The deliberate elevation of a leader through propaganda into an object of mass devotion. The most extreme Chinese example surrounded Mao Zedong, especially during the Cultural Revolution. Later leaders cultivated more restrained versions of the same image-making.",
  "People's_Bank_of_China": "The central bank of the People's Republic of China, which issues the renminbi and sets monetary policy. It manages interest rates, the currency, and the financial system under the direction of the state. It is one of the most powerful central banks in the world.",
  "National_People's_Congress": "China's highest organ of state power and its national legislature, with nearly three thousand delegates. Formally it passes laws and approves leaders, the budget, and major policy. In practice it ratifies decisions made by the Communist Party.",
  "State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China": "China's chief executive body, equivalent to a cabinet, headed by the premier. It runs the ministries and oversees the day-to-day administration of the country. It implements policy set by the Communist Party leadership.",
  "Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party": "The small group at the very top of Chinese politics, usually five to nine members. It is the real centre of decision-making, led by the party general secretary. Its membership is settled through elite bargaining at party congresses.",
  "Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party": "The body of around two dozen senior leaders that directs the Communist Party between Central Committee meetings. From its ranks comes the still more powerful Standing Committee. It sits at the apex of China's political system.",
  "Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party": "The large body, numbering a few hundred members, that formally governs the Communist Party between its congresses. It elects the Politburo and ratifies major decisions. In practice power flows from its top leaders downward.",
  "Central_Military_Commission_(China)": "The body that commands China's armed forces, the People's Liberation Army. Its chairmanship is the key source of military power, normally held by the paramount leader. Control of it is essential to control of the state.",
  "General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party": "The highest office in the Communist Party and, in practice, the most powerful position in China. The holder leads the Politburo and its Standing Committee and is normally the country's paramount leader. The title replaced 'chairman' after the Mao era.",
  "Paramount_leader": "An informal term for the most powerful figure in Chinese politics, who may hold power through party, state, and military posts. The role passed from Mao Zedong to Deng Xiaoping and on to later leaders. It reflects the reality that authority rests with a single person atop the party.",
  "President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China": "The head of state of China, a largely ceremonial office usually held together with the party leadership. Since the post carries little independent power, its weight comes from the other titles its holder wields. Term limits on it were removed in 2018.",
  "Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China": "The head of government of China, leading the State Council and overseeing the economy and administration. Ranking below the party general secretary, the premier manages day-to-day governance. The office has been held by figures from Zhou Enlai to recent reformers.",
  "Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China": "The fundamental law of the Chinese state, first adopted in 1954 and several times rewritten. It sets out the structure of government and citizens' rights while affirming the leading role of the Communist Party. Its 2018 revision removed presidential term limits.",
  "World_Trade_Organization": "The international body that sets and enforces the rules of global trade. China joined in 2001, a milestone that accelerated its integration into the world economy. Membership opened markets to Chinese exports and bound China to trade commitments.",
  "Common_prosperity": "A policy slogan revived under Xi Jinping calling for narrowing China's wide gaps in wealth. It frames efforts to curb excesses among the rich and spread the gains of growth more broadly. Critics question how far it will reshape the economy.",
  "Socialism": "A political and economic outlook favouring collective or state ownership and the reduction of inequality. China's Communist Party claims the socialist mantle even as it embraces markets, calling its model 'socialism with Chinese characteristics.' The tension between the two shapes its politics.",

  // ----- peoples & wider world -----
  "Xiongnu": "A powerful confederation of nomadic peoples on the steppe north of China around the Han era. Their raids prompted the building of walls and the Han's costly Central Asian wars. Their origins and later fate remain debated by historians.",
  "Mongolia": "A landlocked country on the steppe north of China, homeland of the Mongols who once conquered much of Eurasia. Long under Chinese and then Soviet influence, it is today an independent democracy. It is distinct from China's Inner Mongolia region.",
  "Japan": "An East Asian island nation whose history is deeply entwined with China's. It borrowed Chinese writing, Buddhism, and statecraft in early times, then in the modern era invaded and occupied much of China. The two remain major neighbours and rivals.",
  "India": "A vast South Asian civilization and modern nation, long linked to China by trade and the spread of Buddhism. Pilgrims such as Xuanzang travelled there for scriptures. Today it is China's most populous neighbour and a strategic rival.",
  "East_Asia": "The region of the world centred on China, Japan, Korea, and their neighbours. Bound for centuries by shared use of Chinese characters, Confucianism, and Buddhism, it formed a common cultural sphere. It is now one of the most economically dynamic parts of the globe.",
  "Eunuch": "A castrated male servant who staffed the inner court of imperial China. Trusted with access to the emperor and his harem, eunuchs sometimes amassed great political power and provoked scandal. Their influence is a recurring theme in dynastic history.",
  "Capitalism": "An economic system based on private ownership, markets, and the pursuit of profit. China rejected it after 1949 but adopted many of its features through reform after 1978. The result is a hybrid the party calls a socialist market economy.",
  "Market_economy": "An economy in which prices, production, and investment are guided largely by supply and demand rather than the state. China shifted toward this model after 1978 while keeping strong state control of key sectors. The mix defines its socialist market economy.",
  "Rice": "The staple grain of southern China and much of Asia, central to its diet and economy for millennia. Wet-rice farming supported dense populations and shaped the landscape of paddies and terraces. Its cultivation underpinned the wealth of the Yangtze region."
});

